{"title_page": "ShiftyLook", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = ShiftyLook\n| logo = Shiftylook_logo.svg\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| foundation = March 9, 2012\n| defunct = September 2014\n| fate = Closed by [[Bandai Namco Entertainment|Namco Bandai Games]]\n| industry = [[Comic]]\n| products = [[Webcomics]]\n| parent = [[Bandai Namco Holdings]]\n| homepage = [https://web.archive.org/web/20140821115627/http://shiftylook.com/ www.shiftylook.com]\n}}\n'''ShiftyLook''' was a subsidiary of [[Bandai Namco Holdings]] that was focused on revitalizing older [[Namco]] franchises, with their first step being [[video game webcomic]]s based on the company's various franchises. The subsidiary later offered [[webtoon]]s, [[anime]], playable games, music, [[message boards]], and [[graphic novels]] as well. ShiftyLook regularly held substantial exhibitions at large US comics conventions, having a major booth presences and holding large giveaways of promotional merchandise.<ref name=Publishers>{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/comics/article/61381-shiftylook-webcomics-site-to-shut-down.html|work=[[Publishers Weekly]]|title=ShiftyLook Webcomics Site to Shut Down|last=Reid|first=Calvin|date=2014-03-11}}</ref>\n\nShiftyLook shut down on September 30, 2014.\n\n==History==\nShiftyLook was headed by editor-in-chief Robert Pereyda. The idea behind the company was to revive Namco's more obscure, dormant video game franchises for mediums such as webcomics and animations. Pereyda believed that entertainment formats like webcomics were largely successful, and that if these intellectual properties become popular through them, it could garner more interest in those series and make Namco Bandai interested in creating new games for them.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> Namco Bandai also believed that ShiftyLook was a venue for content creators to collaborate on projects, and to establish working relations with artists and developers for future projects. In an interview with CRB.com, Pereyda stated: \"Basically, what we're doing is taking a look at stuff that's forgotten IPs, stuff that's sleeping, stuff that -- just to be honest -- some people don't care about and thinking what we can do with it. This is a big system and we know that not everything's going to succeed, but if some of them can make it to the big time, we've done a good job. We're casting a really wide net. We're doing different styles, different artists, different kinds of titles, just filling out a whole matrix of different things we can do and then seeing where that goes.\" If the webcomics were successful, Pereyda hoped that content such as merchandise and print versions would be available as well.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\">{{cite web |last1=Sunu |first1=Steve |title=Namco Bandai Gives a ShiftyLook to Comics |url=https://www.cbr.com/namco-bandai-gives-a-shiftylook-to-comics/ |website=[[CBR.com]] |accessdate=23 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423185552/https://www.cbr.com/namco-bandai-gives-a-shiftylook-to-comics/ |archivedate=23 March 2020 |date=9 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ShiftyLook old logo.svg|thumb|left|The old ShiftyLook logo]]\nShiftyLook officially launched on March 9, 2012.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> Five webcomics were announced to begin production under the company; ''Bravoman'', ''Xevious'', ''Sky Kid'', ''Rocket Fox'', and ''Alien Confidential: Black and White''. Comics were made available for free on the website, all without advertisements aside from those for Bandai Namco's other projects.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> In June 2012, ShiftyLook announced that Japanese manga artist Hitoshi Ariga would begin work on a webcomic based on ''Klonoa'', becoming the first ShiftyLook comic created outside North America.<ref name=Klonoa>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-14/big-o-hitoshi-ariga-draws-klonoa-webcomic-for-shiftylook|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Big O's Hitoshi Ariga Draws Klonoa Webcomic for ShiftyLook|date=2012-07-14}}</ref> To increase their viewerbase, ShiftyLook regularly attended fan conventions in their own booth, where they featured artists behind some of their comics as well as merchandise. A YouTube channel was launched in 2013, featuring short animated series based on ''Bravoman'' and ''Mappy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2012/07/14/shiftylook-moves-into-cartoons-bravoman-jim-zub-scott-kurtz-and-more/|work=[[Bleeding Cool]]|title=ShiftyLook Moves Into Cartoons \u2013 Bravoman, Jim Zub, Scott Kurtz And More|last=Johnston|first=Rich|date=2012-07-14}}</ref> The same year, Namco Bandai released an endless runner game based on ''Bravoman'', titled ''Bravoman: Binja Bash!'', for iOS and Android devices. ShiftyLook also published ''Wonder Momo: Typhoon Booster'', a sequel to ''Wonder Momo'' developed by [[WayForward]], and ''Namco High'', a comical dating simulator game designed by ''[[Homestuck]]'' creator [[Andrew Hussie]]. A five episode anime series based on ''Wonder Momo'' began in January 2014 on [[Crunchyroll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-01-29/wonder-momo-game-spawns-web-anime-by-graphinica-and-new-game|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Wonder Momo Game Spawns Web Anime by Graphinica & New Game|last=2014-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2014/03/10/namco-bandais-shiftylook-ends-later-this-month|work=[[Crunchyroll]] News|title=Namco Bandai's ShiftyLook Ends Later This Month|last=Saabedra|first=Humberto|date=2014-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2014, ShiftyLook announced that their site would no longer be updated beginning March 20, and by September 30 the company and website would be shut down entirely. They also announced that their YouTube channel, mobile games, and other digital merchandise would be pulled.<ref name=Polygon /> The shutdown was announced by company executive Casy Casoni, who said that ShiftyLook \"battled the video games abyss and won, which means it's time for us to move on and let the hit-makers play with some new toys.\" Before the company's closure, [[Udon Entertainment]] published hardcover books for ''Bravoman'', ''Katamari'', and ''Wonder Momo'' that featured the first 100 strips. A print version of ''Galaga'' was announced but never released.\n\n==List of webcomics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" |-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Authors\n! scope=\"col\" | Original game\n! scope=\"col\" | Start date\n! scope=\"col\" | Source\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Alien Confidential: Black and White''\n| \n| ''Alien Confidential''\n| \n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Bravoman#ShiftyLook media|Bravoman: Super-Unequalled Hero of Excellence]]''\n| Matt Moylan and Dax Gordine\n| ''[[Bravoman]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-03-09}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Dig Dug''\n| Various\n| ''[[Dig Dug]]''\n| {{date table sorting|May 2012}}\n| <ref name=DigDug>{{cite web|url=http://comicsalliance.com/dig-dug-shiftylook-webcomic-project/ |work=[[Comics Alliance]] |title=Shiftylook Celebrating 30 Years of \u2018Dig Dug\u2019 With Anniversary Webcomic Collaboration |last=Goellner |first=Caleb |date=2012-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208135934/http://comicsalliance.com/dig-dug-shiftylook-webcomic-project/ |archivedate=2015-12-08 }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Dragon Spirit''\n| [[Jim Zub]] and Erik Zo\n| ''[[Dragon Spirit]]''\n| {{date table sorting|September 2012}}\n| <ref name=GollyGhostDragonSpirit>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/shiftylook-webcomics-web-cartoons-bravoman/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=Shiftylook Announces New Webcomics and Web Cartoons|last=McMillan|first=Graeme|date=2012-07-19}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Galaga''\n| [[Ryan North]], [[Christopher Hastings]], Anthony Clark\n| ''[[Galaga]]''\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicsalliance.com/best-comic-books-of-2013-part-2/|work=[[ComicsAlliance]]|title=The Best Comic Books of 2013, Part Two|date=2013-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Golly! Ghost!''\n| [[Chris Eliopoulos]]\n| ''[[Golly! Ghost!]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012}}\n| <ref name=GollyGhostDragonSpirit />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Katamari''\n| Alex Culang, Raynato Castro\n| ''[[Katamari Damacy]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-09-17}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/katamari-comic-shiftylook/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=New 'Katamari' Comic Launches Today on Shiftylook|last=Goellner|first=Caleb|date=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Klonoa: Dream Traveller of Noctis Sol''\n| [[Jim Zub]], Hitoshi Ariga\n| ''[[Klonoa]]''\n| {{date table sorting|August 2012}}\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Legend of the Valkyrie''\n| [[Jimmy Palmiotti]], [[Justin Gray]]\n| ''[[Valkyrie no Densetsu]]''\n| {{date table sorting|June 2012}}\n| <ref name=TimeCrisis />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Rapid Thunder''\n| [[Jimmy Palmiotti]], Juan Santacruz\n| ''[[Rolling Thunder (arcade game)|Rolling Thunder]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-05-02}}\n| <ref name=CBR>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=38268|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|title=\"Rolling Thunder\" and \"Wonder Momo\" Come to ShiftyLook as Webcomics|date=2012-04-19}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Rocket Fox''\n|\n| ''Rocket Fox''\n| March 9, 2012\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Scar''\n| Edmund Shern\n| ''[[Genpei T\u014dma Den]]''\n|\n| <ref name=DigDug />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Sky Kid''\n| Jeff \"Chamba\" Cruz\n| ''[[Sky Kid]]''\n| March 9, 2012\n|<ref name=DigDug />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''The Five-Dimensional Adventures of Dirk Davies''\n| Ben McCool\n| ''[[Warp & Warp]]''\n|\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Time Crisis''\n| [[Marv Wolfman]], JJ Kirby\n| ''[[Time Crisis]]''\n| Cancelled\n| <ref name=TimeCrisis>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2012-05-26/namco-bandai-shiftylook-to-launch-time-crisis-valkyrie-webcomics|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Namco Bandai's ShiftyLook to Launch Time Crisis, Valkyrie Webcomics|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|date=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Tower of Babel''\n| [[Sam Logan]] and Shannon Campbell\n| ''[[Tower of Babel (1986 video game)|Tower of Babel]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2013}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2013-07-22/shiftylook-announces-tower-of-babel-webcomic-with-sam-logan-and-shannon-campbell|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=ShiftyLook Announces Tower of Babel Webcomic With Sam Logan and Shannon Campbell|date=2013-07-23}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Wagan Land''\n| Matt Moylan and Rob Porter\n| ''[[Wagan Land]]''\n| {{date table sorting|December 2012}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/shiftylook-adds-wagan-land-to-webcomic-lineup/|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|title=ShiftyLook adds ''Wagan Land'' to webcomic lineup|last=Alverson|first=Bridgit|date=2012-12-27}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Wonder Momo: Battle Idol''\n| [[Jim Zub]], Erik Ko, and Omar Dogan\n| ''[[Wonder Momo]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-05-15}}\n| <ref name=CBR />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Xevious''\n| [[Mike Costa]] and [[Mike Norton]]\n| ''[[Xevious]]''\n| March 9, 2012\n| <ref name=DigDug /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/namco-bandai-shiftylook-webcomics/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=Namco Bandai Reviving Vintage Games as Webcomics Via ShiftyLook|last=Goellner|first=Caleb|date=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Closure==\nOn March 10, 2014, they announced that the site would stop updating ten days later on March 20, and the server would be shut down after September 30 the same year. Some other digital merchandise also became unavailable that year.<ref name=Polygon>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/3/10/5490210/namco-high-studio-shiftylook-is-shutting-its-doors|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Namco High studio ShiftyLook is shutting its doors|last=Gera|first=Emily|date=2014-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shiftylook.com/news/post/newsletter20140310?lang=en|publisher=ShiftyLook|title=ShiftyLook's Next Step|last=Pereyda|first=Rob|date=2014-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314055921/http://www.shiftylook.com/news/post/newsletter20140310?lang=en|archive-date=2014-03-14 }}</ref> The shutdown was announced by ShiftyLook's  Casy Casoni, who wrote: \"now that we have successfully revived so many franchises, the heavy lifting is completed \u2013 and so is our work. We battled the video games abyss and won, which means it's time for us to move on and let the hit-makers play with some new toys.\" Calvin Reid of ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote that the ShiftLook model for building audiences and reviving properties \"looks to have failed overall,\" as only a few of the properties (notably ''Wonder Momo'' and ''Bravoman'') had gained sufficient popularity.<ref name=Publishers />\n\n[[Udon Entertainment]] CEO Matt Moylan, who provided a large quantity of ShiftyLook's online content and wrote 300 strips of the ''Bravoman'' webcomic, wrote that his work for ShiftyLook was \"one of the most creatively rewarding experiences [he has] ever had in comics.\" Moylan stated that Bandai Namco likely invested too much funds into ShiftyLook up front and that plans to monetize its productions did not materialize until it was too late. Udon published [[graphic novel]] adaptations of two ShiftyLook webcomics as the subsidiary was shutting down: ''Bravoman: Super Unequaled Hero of Excellence'' and ''Wonder Momo: Battle Idol''.<ref name=Bleeding>{{cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2014/03/10/shiftylook-closes-but-udon-to-keep-their-comics-going-if-they-can/|work=[[Bleeding Cool]]|title=ShiftyLook Closes \u2013 But Udon To Keep Their Comics Going If They Can|last=Johnston|first=Rich|date=2014-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Namco Generations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Bandai Namco Holdings}}\n\n[[Category:Webcomics]]\n[[Category:Webcomic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Former Bandai Namco Holdings subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Works based on Bandai Namco video games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2014]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = ShiftyLook\n| logo = Shiftylook_logo.svg\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| foundation = March 9, 2012\n| defunct = September 2014\n| fate = Closed by [[Bandai Namco Entertainment|Namco Bandai Games]]\n| industry = \n| products = [[Webcomics]]\n| parent = [[Bandai Namco Holdings]]\n| homepage = \n}}\n'''''ShiftyLook''''' was a subsidiary of [[Bandai Namco Holdings]] that was focused on revitalizing older [[Namco]] franchises, with their first step being [[video game webcomic]]s based on the company's various franchises. The subsidiary later offered [[webtoon]]s, [[anime]], playable games, music, [[message boards]], and [[graphic novels]] as well. ShiftyLook regularly held substantial exhibitions at large US comics conventions, having a major booth presences and holding large giveaways of promotional merchandise.<ref name=Publishers>{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/comics/article/61381-shiftylook-webcomics-site-to-shut-down.html|work=[[Publishers Weekly]]|title=ShiftyLook Webcomics Site to Shut Down|last=Reid|first=Calvin|date=2014-03-11}}</ref>\n\nShiftyLook shut down on September 30, 2014.\n\n==History==\nShiftyLook was headed by editor-in-chief Robert Pereyda. The idea behind the company was to revive Namco's more obscure, dormant video game franchises for mediums such as webcomics and animations. Pereyda believed that entertainment formats like webcomics were largely successful, and that if these intellectual properties become popular through them, it could garner more interest in those series and make Namco Bandai interested in creating new games for them.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> Namco Bandai also believed that ShiftyLook was a venue for content creators to collaborate on projects, and to establish working relations with artists and developers for future projects. In an interview with CRB.com, Pereyda stated: \"Basically, what we're doing is taking a look at stuff that's forgotten IPs, stuff that's sleeping, stuff that -- just to be honest -- some people don't care about and thinking what we can do with it. This is a big system and we know that not everything's going to succeed, but if some of them can make it to the big time, we've done a good job. We're casting a really wide net. We're doing different styles, different artists, different kinds of titles, just filling out a whole matrix of different things we can do and then seeing where that goes.\" If webcomics were successful, Pereyda hoped that content such as merchandise and print versions would be available as well.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\">{{cite web |last1=Sunu |first1=Steve |title=Namco Bandai Gives a ShiftyLook to Comics |url=https://www.cbr.com/namco-bandai-gives-a-shiftylook-to-comics/ |website=[[CBR.com]] |accessdate=23 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423185552/https://www.cbr.com/namco-bandai-gives-a-shiftylook-to-comics/ |archivedate=23 March 2020 |date=9 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nShiftyLook officially launched on March 9, 2012.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> Five webcomics were announced to begin production under the company; ''Bravoman'', ''Xevious'', ''Sky Kid'', ''Rocket Fox'', and ''Alien Confidential: Black and White''. Comics were made available for free on the website, all without advertisements aside from those for Bandai Namco's other projects.<ref name=\"CBR Interview\"/> In June 2012, ShiftyLook announced that Japanese manga artist Hitoshi Ariga would begin work on a webcomic based on ''Klonoa'', becoming the first ShiftyLook comic created outside North America.<ref name=Klonoa>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-14/big-o-hitoshi-ariga-draws-klonoa-webcomic-for-shiftylook|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Big O's Hitoshi Ariga Draws Klonoa Webcomic for ShiftyLook|date=2012-07-14}}</ref> To increase their viewerbase, ShiftyLook regularly attended fan conventions in their own booth, where they featured artists behind some of their comics as well as merchandise. A YouTube channel was launched in 2013, featuring short animated series based on ''Bravoman'' and ''Mappy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2012/07/14/shiftylook-moves-into-cartoons-bravoman-jim-zub-scott-kurtz-and-more/|work=[[Bleeding Cool]]|title=ShiftyLook Moves Into Cartoons \u2013 Bravoman, Jim Zub, Scott Kurtz And More|last=Johnston|first=Rich|date=2012-07-14}}</ref> The same year, Namco Bandai released an endless runner game based on ''Bravoman'', titled ''Bravoman: Binja Bash!'', for iOS and Android devices. ShiftyLook also published ''Wonder Momo: Typhoon Booster'', a sequel to ''Wonder Momo'' developed by [[WayForward]], and ''Namco High'', a comical dating simulator game designed by ''[[Homestuck]]'' creator [[Andrew Hussie]]. A five episode anime series based on ''Wonder Momo'' began in January 2014 on [[Crunchyroll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-01-29/wonder-momo-game-spawns-web-anime-by-graphinica-and-new-game|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Wonder Momo Game Spawns Web Anime by Graphinica & New Game|last=2014-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2014/03/10/namco-bandais-shiftylook-ends-later-this-month|work=[[Crunchyroll]] News|title=Namco Bandai's ShiftyLook Ends Later This Month|last=Saabedra|first=Humberto|date=2014-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2014, ShiftyLook announced that their site would no longer be updated beginning March 20, and by September 30 the company and website would be shut down entirely. They also announced that their YouTube channel, mobile games, and other digital merchandise would be pulled.<ref name=Polygon /> The shutdown was announced by company executive Casy Casoni, who said that ShiftyLook \"battled the video games abyss and won, which means it's time for us to move on and let the hit-makers play with some new toys.\" Before the company's closure, [[Udon Entertainment]] published hardcover books for ''Bravoman'' and ''Wonder Momo'' that featured the first 100 strips. Print versions of ''Galaga'' and ''Katamari'' were also announced, but were never released.\n\n==List of webcomics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" |-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Authors\n! scope=\"col\" | Original game\n! scope=\"col\" | Start date\n! scope=\"col\" | Source\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Alien Confidential: Black and White''\n| \n| ''Alien Confidential''\n| \n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Bravoman#ShiftyLook media|Bravoman: Super-Unequalled Hero of Excellence]]''\n| Matt Moylan and Dax Gordine\n| ''[[Bravoman]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-03-09}}\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Dig Dug''\n| Various\n| ''[[Dig Dug]]''\n| {{date table sorting|May 2012}}\n| <ref name=DigDug>{{cite web|url=http://comicsalliance.com/dig-dug-shiftylook-webcomic-project/ |work=[[Comics Alliance]] |title=Shiftylook Celebrating 30 Years of \u2018Dig Dug\u2019 With Anniversary Webcomic Collaboration |last=Goellner |first=Caleb |date=2012-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208135934/http://comicsalliance.com/dig-dug-shiftylook-webcomic-project/ |archivedate=2015-12-08 }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Dragon Spirit''\n| [[Jim Zub]] and Erik Zo\n| ''[[Dragon Spirit]]''\n| {{date table sorting|September 2012}}\n| <ref name=GollyGhostDragonSpirit>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/shiftylook-webcomics-web-cartoons-bravoman/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=Shiftylook Announces New Webcomics and Web Cartoons|last=McMillan|first=Graeme|date=2012-07-19}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Galaga''\n| [[Ryan North]], [[Christopher Hastings]], Anthony Clark\n| ''[[Galaga]]''\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicsalliance.com/best-comic-books-of-2013-part-2/|work=[[ComicsAlliance]]|title=The Best Comic Books of 2013, Part Two|date=2013-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Golly! Ghost!''\n| [[Chris Eliopoulos]]\n| ''[[Golly! Ghost!]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012}}\n| <ref name=GollyGhostDragonSpirit />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Katamari''\n| Alex Culang, Raynato Castro\n| ''[[Katamari Damacy]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-09-17}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/katamari-comic-shiftylook/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=New 'Katamari' Comic Launches Today on Shiftylook|last=Goellner|first=Caleb|date=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Klonoa: Dream Traveller of Noctis Sol''\n| [[Jim Zub]], Hitoshi Ariga\n| ''[[Klonoa]]''\n| {{date table sorting|August 2012}}\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Legend of the Valkyrie''\n| [[Jimmy Palmiotti]], [[Justin Gray]]\n| ''[[Valkyrie no Densetsu]]''\n| {{date table sorting|June 2012}}\n| <ref name=TimeCrisis />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Rapid Thunder''\n| [[Jimmy Palmiotti]], Juan Santacruz\n| ''[[Rolling Thunder (arcade game)|Rolling Thunder]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-05-02}}\n| <ref name=CBR>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=38268|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|title=\"Rolling Thunder\" and \"Wonder Momo\" Come to ShiftyLook as Webcomics|date=2012-04-19}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Rocket Fox''\n|\n| ''Rocket Fox''\n| March 9, 2012\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Scar''\n| Edmund Shern\n| ''[[Genpei T\u014dma Den]]''\n|\n| <ref name=DigDug />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Sky Kid''\n| Jeff \"Chamba\" Cruz\n| ''[[Sky Kid]]''\n| March 9, 2012\n|<ref name=DigDug />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''The Five-Dimensional Adventures of Dirk Davies''\n| Ben McCool\n| ''[[Warp & Warp]]''\n|\n| <ref name=Klonoa />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Time Crisis''\n| [[Marv Wolfman]], JJ Kirby\n| ''[[Time Crisis]]''\n| Cancelled\n| <ref name=TimeCrisis>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2012-05-26/namco-bandai-shiftylook-to-launch-time-crisis-valkyrie-webcomics|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=Namco Bandai's ShiftyLook to Launch Time Crisis, Valkyrie Webcomics|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|date=2012-05-26}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Tower of Babel''\n| [[Sam Logan]] and Shannon Campbell\n| ''[[Tower of Babel (1986 video game)|Tower of Babel]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2013}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2013-07-22/shiftylook-announces-tower-of-babel-webcomic-with-sam-logan-and-shannon-campbell|work=[[Anime News Network]]|title=ShiftyLook Announces Tower of Babel Webcomic With Sam Logan and Shannon Campbell|date=2013-07-23}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Wagan Land''\n| Matt Moylan and Rob Porter\n| ''[[Wagan Land]]''\n| {{date table sorting|December 2012}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/shiftylook-adds-wagan-land-to-webcomic-lineup/|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|title=ShiftyLook adds ''Wagan Land'' to webcomic lineup|last=Alverson|first=Bridgit|date=2012-12-27}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Wonder Momo: Battle Idol''\n| [[Jim Zub]], Erik Ko, and Omar Dogan\n| ''[[Wonder Momo]]''\n| {{date table sorting|2012-05-15}}\n| <ref name=CBR />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''Xevious''\n| [[Mike Costa]] and [[Mike Norton]]\n| ''[[Xevious]]''\n| March 9, 2012\n| <ref name=DigDug /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicsalliance.com/namco-bandai-shiftylook-webcomics/|work=[[Comics Alliance]]|title=Namco Bandai Reviving Vintage Games as Webcomics Via ShiftyLook|last=Goellner|first=Caleb|date=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Closure==\nOn March 10, 2014, they announced that the site would stop updating ten days later on March 20, and the server would be shut down after September 30 the same year. Some other digital merchandise also became unavailable that year.<ref name=Polygon>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/3/10/5490210/namco-high-studio-shiftylook-is-shutting-its-doors|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|title=Namco High studio ShiftyLook is shutting its doors|last=Gera|first=Emily|date=2014-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shiftylook.com/news/post/newsletter20140310?lang=en|publisher=ShiftyLook|title=ShiftyLook's Next Step|last=Pereyda|first=Rob|date=2014-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314055921/http://www.shiftylook.com/news/post/newsletter20140310?lang=en|archive-date=2014-03-14 }}</ref> The shutdown was announced by ShiftyLook's  Casy Casoni, who wrote: \"now that we have successfully revived so many franchises, the heavy lifting is completed \u2013 and so is our work. We battled the video games abyss and won, which means it's time for us to move on and let the hit-makers play with some new toys.\" Calvin Reid of ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote that the ShiftLook model for building audiences and reviving properties \"looks to have failed overall,\" as only a few of the properties (notably ''Wonder Momo'' and ''Bravoman'') had gained sufficient popularity.<ref name=Publishers />\n\n[[Udon Entertainment]] CEO Matt Moylan, who provided a large quantity of ShiftyLook's online content and wrote 300 strips of the ''Bravoman'' webcomic, wrote that his work for ShiftyLook was \"one of the most creatively rewarding experiences [he has] ever had in comics.\" Moylan stated that Bandai Namco likely invested too much funds into ShiftyLook up front and that plans to monetize its productions did not materialize until it was too late. Udon published [[graphic novel]] adaptations of two ShiftyLook webcomics as the subsidiary was shutting down: ''Bravoman: Super Unequaled Hero of Excellence'' and ''Wonder Momo: Battle Idol''.<ref name=Bleeding>{{cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2014/03/10/shiftylook-closes-but-udon-to-keep-their-comics-going-if-they-can/|work=[[Bleeding Cool]]|title=ShiftyLook Closes \u2013 But Udon To Keep Their Comics Going If They Can|last=Johnston|first=Rich|date=2014-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Namco Generations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Bandai Namco Holdings}}\n\n[[Category:Webcomics]]\n[[Category:Webcomic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Former Bandai Namco Holdings subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Works based on Bandai Namco video games]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2014]]\n", "name_user": "Namcokid47", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ShiftyLook"}
{"title_page": "Windjammers (video game)", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Windjammers\n|image         = Windjammers arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = North American Arcade flyer\n|developer     = [[Data East]]<br />[[DotEmu]] <small>(PS4/PSV/Switch)</small>\n|publisher     ={{collapsible list|title=Data East|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[SNK]] <small>(AES/CD)</small><br />[[D4 Enterprise]]<br /><small>(Virtual Console)</small><br />DotEmu, [[Limited Run Games]] <small>(PS4/PSV/Switch)</small>}}\n|producer      = Takaaki Inoue\n|programmer    = Wataru Iida\n|artist        = Makoto Nozu<br />Masateru Inagaki<br />Masayuki Inoshita\n|composer      = Masaaki Iwasaki<br />Seiichi Hamada<br />Tomoyoshi Sato\n|series        = ''Windjammers''\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]], [[Neo Geo CD]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Network]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Virtual Console]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1994 in video gaming|1994]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|WW|17 February 1994}} '''Neo Geo AES'''{{vgrelease|JP|8 April 1994|NA|8 April 1994|EU|8 April 1994}} '''Neo Geo CD'''{{vgrelease|JP|20 January [[1995 in video gaming|1995]]|NA|October [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]}} '''Virtual Console'''{{vgrelease|JP|22 June [[2010 in video gaming|2010]]}} '''PlayStation Network'''{{vgrelease|WW|29 August [[2017 in video gaming|2017]]<ref>https://blog.us.playstation.com/2017/07/17/windjammers-arrives-august-29-on-ps4-ps-vita/</ref>}} '''Nintendo Switch'''{{vgrelease|WW|23 October [[2018 in video gaming|2018]]}}}}\n|genre         = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=10#18474|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n'''''Windjammers'''''{{efn|Known as {{nihongo|'''''Flying Power Disc'''''|\u30d5\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d1\u30ef\u30fc\u30fb\u30c7\u30a3\u30b9\u30af|''Furaingu Paw\u0101 Disuku''||lead=yes}} in Japan.}} is a [[Sports game|sports]] [[arcade game]] released by [[Data East]] on the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo Geo]] arcade system in [[1994 in video gaming|1994]].<ref name=\"B!MDOh!NGw\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3ABeepMD_JP_1994-03.pdf&page=136|title=Oh! Neo Geo Vol. 19 - \u30d5\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d1\u30ef\u30fc\u30fb\u30c7\u30a3\u30b9\u30af|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#BEEP!\u30e1\u30ac\u30c9\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6|Beep! MegaDrive]]|issue=54|publisher=[[SB Creative|SoftBank Creative]]|date=March 1994|page=134|lang=ja}}</ref> The game mechanics are essentially the same as ''[[Pong]]'' or [[air hockey]], where players continuously shoot the disc at the goal zone of the opponent attempting to score. The game can be played against the computer or in a 2 player versus.\n\nA sequel, ''[[Windjammers 2]]'', is planned for release on Nintendo Switch and PC in 2020.<ref>https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-10-23-two-point-hospital-on-consoles-delayed-to-2020</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:NEOGEO Windjammers (Flying Power Disc).png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\nPlayers choose from one of six playable characters, each with their own unique speed and power ratings and special throws. The player maneuvers around his/her side of the court in any of the 8 cardinal directions (allowing for almost fluid movement in any direction). They must act as the defense and offense of their side, blocking the disc from entering the goal zone, and throwing the disc back to the opponent's side attempting to score. Players throw the disc back and forth (with the speed of the disc generally increasing with each throw) until one of them scores a point, which causes the disc to be reset by the referee, who throws it to the player that was scored on so that they can serve. There are yellow and pink zones with the former being worth 3 points and the latter being 5, with the zones positioning varying for each court. Also not catching the disc while it is in the air (described below) is considered a \"Miss\" and gives 2 points to the opponent.\n\n===Defensive play===\nWhile the opponent holds the disc the player acts defensively by trying to grab the disc and therefore stopping it from entering their goal zone. In order to stop the disc the player simply needs to make contact with it. They can walk into the disc or dive for it with a button press (which is done at almost all times due to the high speeds of the disc). Sometimes the disc may be launched into the air, due to the opponent, the net, barriers, or sometimes bouncing off the player's back, in which a target will appear on the court showing the landing spot of the disc, which can be caught by standing on said target.\n\n===Offensive play===\nWhile the player holds the disc they act offensively by trying to throw it into the goal zone of the opponent. The player can not move while holding the disc, and can not hold it for more than a few seconds. The player points with the joystick in the direction he/she wishes to throw the disc, and presses the primary button. The player can throw it either directly at the opponents goal zone or attempt to bounce the disc off the walls, or barriers (if in a court that contains them).\n\n===Winning the game===\nWhen playing against the computer the player plays one match against each character (with the next characters difficulty increasing each time) until all are defeated, thus winning the game, and when playing 2 player versus one match is played between the two players. A match consists of 3 sets that last 30 seconds by default and up to 99 seconds on the arcade version. (with the timer not stopping when a point is scored unlike most sports). A set is won by the player who has the most points at the end of 30 seconds, or if a player reaches 12 points. A tie gives a win to both players. A match is won when the player wins two sets, if players tie in both of the first two sets (giving each of them two wins) the game enters a sudden death round where the first player to score (regardless of the zone value) wins.\n\n==Ports==\nOn June 22, 2010, the game was released on the [[Wii]] [[Virtual Console]] in Japan. Following the bankruptcy of Data East, the intellectual rights for this game were acquired by [[Paon DP]], a mobile company formed by some ex-Data East employees.<ref>[https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/53gwj8/the-story-behind-reviving-obscure-neo-geo-classic-windjammers The Story Behind Reviving Obscure Neo Geo Classic 'Windjammers']</ref><ref>[http://www.vc-neogeo.d4e.co.jp/title_neogeo/flyingpowerdisc/index.html Flying Power Disc Virtual Console information from D4 Enterprise]</ref> It was delisted from the Virtual Console on December 24, 2013, making it the only delisted Neo-Geo game for the Virtual Console.\n\nA port of the game with online multiplayer support was released by [[DotEmu]] for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[PlayStation Vita]] on August 29, 2017, with a [[Nintendo Switch]] version on October 23, 2018.<ref>https://gematsu.com/2018/08/windjammers-coming-to-switch-in-2018</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/Dotemu/status/1031512502708912129</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video 