ognised government of the British colony of [[Southern Rhodesia]] had [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|unilaterally declared independence]] as Rhodesia in 1965, proclaiming Elizabeth II as Queen, but she did not accept the title, nor was it recognised by any other state. Following a [[1969 Rhodesian constitutional referendum|referendum in 1969]], in which 81% voted to abolish the monarchy, a republic was declared in 1970.\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Cambodia.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Cambodia]]\n|[[Norodom Sihanouk]]\n|Later restored (see below).\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of The Gambia.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[History of the Gambia|The Gambia]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Elizabeth II\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1971\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]].\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Guyana.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[History of Guyana#Independence|Guyana]]\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Sierra Leone.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[History of Sierra Leone#Early independence (1961\u20131978)|Sierra Leone]]\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Sri Lanka.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[History of Sri Lanka#Political independence|Ceylon]]\n|1972\n|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]], state name changed into \"Sri Lanka\".\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Afghanistan 1930.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Kingdom of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]\n|[[Mohammed Zahir Shah]]\n|1973\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Coup d'\u00e9tat\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Ethiopia (1897-1936; 1941-1974).svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Ethiopian Empire|Ethiopia]]\n|[[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia|Haile Selassie I]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1974\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Greece (1970-1975).svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Kingdom of Greece (Gl\u00fccksburg)|Greece]]\n|[[Constantine II of Greece|Constantine II]]\n|[[1974 Greek republic referendum|referendum]]; official result: 69% against monarchy\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Malta.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Independence Day (Malta)|Malta]]\n|Elizabeth II\n|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]].\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Laos (1952-1975).svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Kingdom of Laos|Laos]]\n|[[Savang Vatthana]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1975\n|Communist takeover\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Sikkim (1967-1975).svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Sikkim]]\n|[[Palden Thondup Namgyal]]\n|[[1975 Sikkimese monarchy referendum|Referendum]]; official result: 97% to become a [[state of India]].\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Trinidad and Tobago.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[History of Trinidad and Tobago#20th-century political development|Trinidad and Tobago]]\n|Elizabeth II\n|1976\n|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]].\n|-\n|[[File:State Flag of Iran (1964).svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]]\n|[[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1979\n|[[Iranian Revolution]]\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of the Central African Republic.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Central African Empire|Central Africa]]\n|[[Bokassa I of Central Africa|Bokassa I]]\n|coup d'\u00e9tat\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#eeeeaa;\"|1980s\n|-\n|[[File:Rwenzururu flag.png|31px|border]]\n|[[Kingdom of Rwenzururu|Rwenzururu]]\n|[[Charles Mumbere]]\n|1982\n|Forced to abdicate by the government of Uganda; declaration of independence of Rwenzururu was annulled.\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Fiji.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Fiji]]\n|Elizabeth II\n|1987\n|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]]. [[Elizabeth II]] remained recognized as [[Monarchy of Fiji|Paramount Chief]] by the [[Great Council of Chiefs]] until the council's de-establishment on 14 March 2012.\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#eeeeaa;\"|1990s\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Kuwait.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Republic of Kuwait|Kuwait]]\n|[[Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah]]\n|1990\n|Later restored (see below)\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Mauritius.svg|31px|border]]\n|[[Mauritius]]\n|Elizabeth II\n|1992\n|Abolished [[Commonwealth realm|Commonwealth monarchy]].\n|}\n\n== 21st century ==\n=== Elimination of remaining monarchies ===\nThe bulk of monarchies did not survive the 20th century, those that remained were limited to figurehead status or continued in odd forms such as the Cambodia communist monarchy. One of the few traditional monarchies that remained was the [[Kingdom of Nepal]]. After a series of strange events, [[Gyanendra of Nepal|King Gyanendra's]] monarchy was abolished in May 2008 and replaced with a secular federal republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7424302.stm |title=World &#124; South Asia &#124; Nepal votes to abolish monarchy |publisher=BBC News |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=2011-07-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Monarchies that were abolished, restored, and continue to exist in the 21st century ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Country\n! Year abolished\n! Notes\n! Year restored\n! Years of republic\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of England.svg| 31px|border]] [[File:St Patrick's saltire.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Kingdom of England|England]]\n| 1649\n| [[Commonwealth of England]] established, then Parliament reversed itself and invited the [[The Restoration | return of the monarchy]].\n| 1660\n| 11\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Scotland (1542-2003).svg|31x31px]]\n|Scotland\n|1652\n|[[Scotland under the Commonwealth|Commonwealth]]\n|1660\n|8\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[File:Flag of Spain.svg| 31px|border]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Spain\n| 1873\n| [[First Spanish Republic]] established\n| 1874\n| 1\n|- \n| 1931\n| [[Second Spanish Republic]] established, then 1947 [[Spanish State|restored]] ''([[de jure]])'' under the regency of [[Francisco Franco]]\n| 1975<br /><small>([[de facto]])</small>\n| 44 <small>(16 - ''de jure'')</small>\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of Kuwait.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Kuwait]]\n| 1990\n| A [[Republic of Kuwait]] proclaimed with the support of [[Iraq]]; restored by a United States intervention.\n| 1991\n| 1\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Ankole.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Ankole]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1967\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Four traditional [[Uganda]]n monarchies abolished by government under new constitution of [[Milton Obote]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1993\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 26\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of Buganda.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Buganda]]\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of Bunyoro, Uganda.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Bunyoro]]\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of Toro, Uganda.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Tooro Kingdom|Tooro]]\n|- \n| [[File:Flag of Cambodia.svg| 31px|border]]\n| [[Cambodia]]\n| 1970\n| The [[Khmer Republic]] established and through transformations restored as an [[Cambodia|elective monarchy]].\n| 1993\n| 23\n|- \n| [[File:Rwenzururu flag.png| 31px|border]]\n| [[Rwenzururu region|Rwenzururu]], a part of Uganda\n| 1982\n| 'Reinstated' out of popular support despite no evidence of such a kingdom.<ref>Caleb Mukirane \"Uganda: Rwenzururu Kingdom Has Never Existed, \" all Africa, 3 October 2007, last accessed 28 December 2019. https://allafrica.com/stories/200710040061.html</ref>\n| 2009<br /><small>([[de facto]])</small>\n| 27\n|}\n\nMany other monarchies continue to exist in the 21st century, never having been abolished.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Abdication#List|List of Abdications by Date]]\n*[[List of countries by date of transition to republican system of government]]\n*[[List of monarchy referendums]]\n*[[List of monarchs who lost their thrones before the 17th century]]\n*[[List of monarchs who lost their thrones in the 17th century]]\n*[[List of monarchs who lost their thrones in the 18th century]]\n*[[List of monarchs who lost their thrones in the 19th century]]\n*[[List of extinct states]]\n*[[Debate on the monarchy in Canada]]\n*[[Republicanism in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Republicanism in Norway]]\n*[[2009 Saint Vincent and the Grenadines constitutional referendum]]\n*[[2008 Tuvaluan constitutional referendum]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Republicanism}}\n{{Former Monarchies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abolished Monarchy}}\n[[Category:Monarchy]]\n[[Category:Republicanism]]\n[[Category:Abolition|Monarchy]]\n", "name_user": "50.106.220.235", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abolition_of_monarchy"}
{"title_page": "Helen Whately", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Helen Whately\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Helen Whately MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Department of Health and Social Care (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Social Care]]\n| term_start = 13 February 2020\n| term_end = \n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| predecessor =[[Caroline Dinenage]]  \n| successor =\n| office1 = [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the Arts, Heritage and Tourism]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start1 = 10 September 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/helen-whately|title=Helen Whately MP|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017221121/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/helen-whately|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| term_end1 = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Rebecca Pow]]\n| successor1 = [[Nigel Huddleston]]\n| office2 = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Deputy Chair of the Conservative Party]]\n| leader2 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start2 = 17 April 2019\n| term_end2 = 10 September 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[James Cleverly]]\n| successor2 = [[Paul Scully]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]]\n| term_start3 = 8 May 2015\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]]\n| successor3 = \n| majority3 = 21,976 (43.6%)<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700|publisher=BBC News|title=Faversham & Mid Kent|accessdate=13 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411094752/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_name = Helen Olivia Bicknell Lightwood\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|6|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Marcus Whately|2005}}\n| children = 3\n| alma_mater = [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n| website = {{url|helenwhately.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Helen Olivia Bicknell Whately'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9123}}</ref> (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Lightwood''';<ref>{{cite news |url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/83953/whately |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 August 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2017 |title=Whately |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205028/http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/83953/whately |archivedate=11 November 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/121365/whately |title=Whately |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 August 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021213/http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/121365/whately |archivedate=12 November 2017 }}</ref> born 23 June 1976) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who was appointed  [[Minister of State]] (Minister for Care) at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]] on 13 February 2020 and [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]] since 2015. She also served as Deputy Chair of the Conservative Party.\n\nShe was born in [[Norwich]]. Her early education was at the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Westminster School]] in London. After graduating from the [[University of Oxford]], she worked as a management consultant trainee at [[PriceWaterhouseCoopers]]. From 2007 to 2015, she worked as a management consultant at [[McKinsey & Company]] in their healthcare division.  She was [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism]] from 10 September 2019 until 13 Feb 2020. \n\n==Early life and career==\nHelen Olivia Bicknell Lightwood<ref name=FMP/> was born in [[Norwich]] on 23 June 1976, and grew up near [[Redhill, Surrey]]. Both her parents worked as doctors.<ref name=MyParl>{{cite web |url=http://myparliament.info/member/4527 |title=Biography for Helen Whately |publisher=MyParliament |accessdate=22 April 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428235943/http://myparliament.info/member/4527 |archivedate=28 April 2017 }}</ref><ref name=Down>{{cite news |title=Personality Profile |pages=8\u20139 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109173126/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/_img/pics/pdf_1483564629.pdf |archivedate=9 November 2017 |last=Finlay |first=Simon |url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/_img/pics/pdf_1483564629.pdf |work=Mid Kent Living |accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Surrey>{{cite news |url=http://www.surreycomet.co.uk/news/1358635.conservatives_are_putting_faith_in_youthful_whately/ |title=Conservatives are putting faith in youthful Whately |date=30 April 2007 |work=Surrey Comet |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124083816/http://www.surreycomet.co.uk/news/1358635.conservatives_are_putting_faith_in_youthful_whately/ |archivedate=24 November 2015 }}</ref> She was educated at [[Woldingham School]], Surrey, a day and boarding schools for girls aged 11-18; before entering the [[sixth form]] at the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Westminster School]] in London.<ref name=Down/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/general-election-candidates-for-faversham-35166/ |title=Who wants your vote in Faversham and Mid Kent? |publisher=Kent Online |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815083143/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/general-election-candidates-for-faversham-35166/ |archivedate=15 August 2015 }}</ref> During her school years she undertook work experience in hospitals, with the intention of following her parents into a medical career, but Whately commented in her maiden speech as MP that it instead incentivised her to pursue a career in which she could improve healthcare as a whole.<ref name=maiden/>\n\nAfter leaving school, she taught English in rural [[Nepal]] for a year.<ref name=Surrey/> Lightwood studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]].<ref name=Down/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/Alumni/Prominent-alumni.aspx |title=LMH, Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Prominent Alumni |accessdate=22 May 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512181442/http://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/Alumni/Prominent-alumni.aspx |archivedate=12 May 2015 }}</ref> During her time at Oxford she was a member of debating society the [[Oxford Union]], but she did not have any interest in student politics, later saying that she felt that it \"did not seem to be about getting stuff done\".<ref name=Down/>\n\nAfter university, she worked at [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] for two years as a management consultant trainee before working at [[AOL]] where Lightwood was involved in setting up their internet film service.<ref name=Surrey/><ref>{{cite news|title=A future Tory Cabinet ... at least according to Tatler |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/a-future-tory-cabinet-at-least-according-to-tatler-6898834.html |work=London Evening Standard |date=9 September 2008 |last1=Hopkirk |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Mendick |first2=Robert |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113013809/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/a-future-tory-cabinet-at-least-according-to-tatler-6898834.html |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref><ref name=Helen/> After this she worked as a media policy advisor for the then Shadow Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport and Conservative Party MP [[Hugo Swire]]. This experience inspired her to pursue a political career.<ref name=Down/> In 2008, British society magazine ''[[Tatler]]'' selected Whately as one of ten young rising stars of the Conservative Party and tipped her as a future Health Secretary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Society magazine Tatler unveils line-up of 'top Tory totty'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2711375/Society-magazine-Tatler-unveils-line-up-of-top-Tory-totty.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 September 2008|accessdate=27 June 2019|last=Singh|first=Anita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626232138/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2711375/Society-magazine-Tatler-unveils-line-up-of-top-Tory-totty.html|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe unsuccessfully contested the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] in the [[Kingston and Surbiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston and Surbiton]] constituency for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], losing to the incumbent [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Ed Davey]] by 7,560 votes (13.3%).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c43.stm|title=Kingston & Surbiton|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701045211/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c43.stm|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2007 to 2015, Whately worked as an engagement manager for the management consultancy firm [[McKinsey & Company]] in their healthcare division.<ref name=Helen/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/helen-whately/1202337.bio |work=Health Service Journal |title=Helen Whately |accessdate=21 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828185737/https://www.hsj.co.uk/helen-whately/1202337.bio |archivedate=28 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nWhately was selected by the Conservative Party in February 2015 to contest the [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]] seat in an all-women shortlist.<ref name=\"kentonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/tory-candidate-picked-for-faversham-32433/ |title=Helen Whately to replace Sir Hugh Robertson as conservative candidate for Faversham and Mid Kent |publisher=Kent Online |accessdate=7 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511022350/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/tory-candidate-picked-for-faversham-32433 |archivedate=11 May 2015 |date=25 February 2015 }}</ref> The constituency's previous Conservative MP [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]] had chosen in January not to seek re-election.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30824449 |title=Hugh Robertson, former Conservative minister, to stand down |publisher=BBC News |date=15 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115112801/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30824449 |archivedate=15 January 2015 }}</ref> She had also made the shortlist for the [[Wealden (UK Parliament constituency)|Wealden]], [[North East Hampshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Hampshire]], [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]], [[Bury St. Edmunds (UK Parliament constituency)|Bury St. Edmunds]] and [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]] constituencies.<ref name=kentonline/>\n\nShe was elected as MP for Faversham and Mid Kent at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with 24,895 votes (54%) and a majority of 16,652 (36.4%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230161528/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |archivedate=30 December 2016 }}</ref> The constituency is considered as a [[safe seat]], and has been represented by Conservative MPs since its creation in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/favershamandmidkent/ |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=UK Polling Report |accessdate=7 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108093855/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/favershamandmidkent/ |archivedate=8 November 2017 }}</ref> Whately's maiden speech on 2 June focused on the [[National Health Service]].<ref name=maiden>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/maiden-speech |title=Maiden Speech |publisher=Helen Whately |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |last=Whately |first=Helen |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225644/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/maiden-speech |archivedate=28 August 2017 }}</ref> In July, she was chosen to sit on the Commons [[Health Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/helen-whately/4527 |title=Helen Whately MP |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906212133/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/helen-whately/4527 |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref> In December, she voted to support Prime Minister [[David Cameron]]'s plans to carry out airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34987921 |title=Syria strikes: Find out how your MP voted |publisher=BBC News |date=3 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203070703/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34987921 |archivedate=3 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nWhately supported the United Kingdom (UK) remaining within the [[European Union]] (EU) in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|June 2016 membership referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough |first1=Tom |title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence? |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/ |accessdate=11 October 2016 |work=The Spectator |date=16 February 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022111657/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/ |archivedate=22 October 2016 }}</ref> She stated her reason for this was that British membership of the EU meant greater economic growth, security, standards of living for British people, and British influence in international affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/why-im-voting-stay-eu |title=Why I'm voting to stay in the EU |publisher=Helen Whately |date=22 May 2017 |last=Whately |first=Helen |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118221921/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/why-im-voting-stay-eu |archivedate=18 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Whately was appointed as the Parliamentary Private Secretary (PPS) to the International Trade Minister [[Greg Hands]].<ref name=Helen/> In October, she was selected as the Chair of the All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) for Mental Health and of the APPG for Fruit and Vegetable Farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/mental-health.htm |title=All-Party Parliamentary Group on Mental Health |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121932/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/mental-health.htm |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentnews.co.uk/news/helen-whately-elected-chair-of-parliamentary-group-for-mental-health-1-4732737 |title=Helen Whately elected chair of parliamentary group for mental health |publisher=Kent News |last=Pyman |first=Tom |date=12 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193724/http://www.kentnews.co.uk/news/helen-whately-elected-chair-of-parliamentary-group-for-mental-health-1-4732737 |archivedate=19 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124235143/https://www.hortweek.com/new-parliamentary-group-hears-fruit-veg-growers-concerns/fresh-produce/article/1414592 |archivedate=24 November 2017 |url=http://www.hortweek.com/new-parliamentary-group-hears-fruit-veg-growers-concerns/fresh-produce/article/1414592 |work=[[Horticulture Week]] |date=4 November 2016 |title=New parliamentary group hears fruit and veg growers' concerns |accessdate=1 April 2017 |last=McEwan |first=Gavin}}</ref> In February 2017, she voted to support the government's motion for the [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoking of Article 50]] to formally start the process of the UK's withdrawal from the EU. Whately, a \"Remain\" supporter, explained her decision as honouring the result of the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/brexit-lets-use-opportunity-frame-countrys-future |title=Brexit: Let's use this opportunity to frame the country's future |publisher=Helen Whately |last=Whately |first=Helen |date=2 February 2017 |accessdate=3 December 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203155243/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/brexit-lets-use-opportunity-frame-countrys-future |archivedate=3 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Article 50 Brexit vote: Full list of MPs who backed Theresa May starting official EU negotiations&nbsp;\u2014 and those who voted against |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-parliament-mps-vote-brexit-theresa-may-eu-negotiations-labour-conservative-how-voted-a7558291.html |work=The Independent |date=1 February 2017 |accessdate=3 December 2017 |last=Batchelor |first=Tom |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032958/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-parliament-mps-vote-brexit-theresa-may-eu-negotiations-labour-conservative-how-voted-a7558291.html |archivedate=1 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, she faced criticism from some local residents for tweeting enthusiastically about being at the inauguration of President Donald Trump, due to his controversial policies. She responded that she was representing parliamentarians from the UK, and that it was important to build links with key foreign allies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Faversham and Mid Kent MP Helen Whately faces backlash after tweet about Donald Trump's inauguration |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mp-faces-backlash-after-inauguration-119313/ |work=Kent Online |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=22 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015003230/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mp-faces-backlash-after-inauguration-119313/ |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhately held her seat in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]] in June 2017, with 30,390 (61.1%) votes and an increased majority of 17,413 (35%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 June 2017 |archivedate=17 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617084859/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700}}</ref> Following the election she became the PPS to the [[Secretary of State for Education]] and [[Minister for Women and Equalities]], [[Justine Greening]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2017/06/parliamentary-private-secretaries-full-list.html |title=Parliamentary Private Secretaries: full list |publisher=Conservative Home |date=28 June 2017 |accessdate=17 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009063654/https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2017/06/parliamentary-private-secretaries-full-list.html |archivedate=9 October 2017 }}</ref> She also became the chair of the APPG for Health, and Personalised Medicine and continued to be chair of the APPG for Mental Health, and Fruit and Vegetable Farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170928/health.htm |title=Health |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=22 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023120212/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170928/health.htm |archivedate=23 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/personalised-medicine.htm |title=Personalised Medicine |accessdate=9 November 2017 |publisher=parliament.uk |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/personalised-medicine.htm |archivedate=9 November 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/register-171108.pdf |title=Register of All-Party Parliamentary Groups |date=8 November 2017 |pages=462, 504, 621, 677 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021330/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/register-171108.pdf |archivedate=12 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Whately was criticised for accepting several thousand pounds' worth of hospitality from the [[Saudi Arabian government]] before going on to defend its record in a parliamentary debate. The debate followed an urgent question by Liberal Democrat MP [[Tom Brake]] over fears of the imminent execution of 14 men for protest-related offences, including a number who were children at the time of their alleged offences. Whately had urged parliamentarians to \"appreciate that the government of Saudi Arabia are taking to steps to improve their actions on human rights\", but was criticised by an opposition [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP as a \"serial apologist for the regime\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory MPs push 'soft' policy on Saudi executions months after meeting king |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/xxx-1055620181 |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=Middle East Eye |date=18 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042211/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/xxx-1055620181 |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia has paid for nearly a dozen Tory MPs to fly out and visit on 'fact-finding missions' this year |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/saudi-arabia-has-paid-for-nearly-a-dozen-tory-mps-to-fly-out-and-visit-it-so-far-this-year-a6993271.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=20 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042040/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/saudi-arabia-has-paid-for-nearly-a-dozen-tory-mps-to-fly-out-and-visit-it-so-far-this-year-a6993271.html |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, she was appointed as PPS to [[Brandon Lewis]], the [[Minister without portfolio]] and [[Chairman of the Conservative Party|Conservative Party Chair]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676443/PPS_List_January_2018.pdf |title=Parliamentary Private Secretaries January 2018 |publisher=gov.uk |date=January 2018 |accessdate=5 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507003457/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676443/PPS_List_January_2018.pdf |archive-date=7 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/08/james-brokenshire-resigns-northern-ireland-secretary-cabinet-reshuffle|title=Brandon Lewis unveiled as Tory chairman in chaotic reshuffle|work=The Guardian|date=8 January 2018|access-date=8 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108133601/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/08/james-brokenshire-resigns-northern-ireland-secretary-cabinet-reshuffle|archive-date=8 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later in the year, she became Vice Chair of the Conservative Party for Women, after [[Maria Caulfield]] stood down in protest at the Government's approach to Brexit.<ref name=\"resignation\">{{cite news |title=Tory vice-chairs quit over PM's Brexit plan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44785797 |work=BBC News |date=10 July 2018 |access-date=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427143515/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44785797 |archive-date=27 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/kent-mp-handed-vice-chair-role-187073/|title=Faversham and Mid Kent MP Helen Whately named Conservative's vice-chair for women|publisher=Kent Online|date=27 July 2018|accessdate=25 June 2019|last=Pyman|first=Tom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627131627/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/kent-mp-handed-vice-chair-role-187073/|archive-date=27 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Whately voted for the then Prime Minister Theresa May's Brexit withdrawal agreement. She also stated her opposition to a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|referendum on any Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/how-ive-voted-brexit|publisher=Helen Whately|last=Whately|first=Helen|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=13 September 2019|title=How I've voted on Brexit|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405005440/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/how-ive-voted-brexit|archive-date=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 April, Whately was promoted to deputy chair of the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/04/28/tories-braced-local-election-wipeout-deputy-chairman-warns-mounting/|title=Tories braced for local election wipeout as deputy chairman warns of mounting anger on the doorstep|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 April 2019|last=Yorke|first=Harry|accessdate=25 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512113158/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/04/28/tories-braced-local-election-wipeout-deputy-chairman-warns-mounting/|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?id=uk.org.publicwhip/member/41839|publisher=The Public Whip|accessdate=25 June 2019|title=Voting Record \u2014 Helen Whately MP, Faversham and Mid Kent (25398)}}</ref> On 10 September, she was appointed as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] for Arts, Heritage and Tourism by Prime Minister Boris Johnson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-cabinet-reshuffle-mps-ministers-a9099976.html|work=The Independent|date=10 September 2019|title=Boris Johnson has cabinet reshuffle following Brexit-induced resignations|last=Austin|first=Henry|access-date=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911200221/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-cabinet-reshuffle-mps-ministers-a9099976.html|archive-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the December general election, she was re-elected with an increased majority of 21,976 (43.6%)<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn February 2020, Whatley joined the [[Department for Health and Social Care]] as the [[Minister of State for Social Care]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Lydia |last=Catling |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/new-jobs-for-kent-mps-in-government-reshuffle-222102/ |title=Prime Minister Boris Johnson given MPs Helen Whately and Kelly Tolhurst new jobs in government |publisher=Kent Online |date=14 February 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> \nIn April 2020, Whateley became a regular rabbit in headlights, crumbling under the questioning of GMB\u2019s Piers Morgan. \n\n===Campaigns===\nIn 2017, she campaigned for the repeal of the [[Hunting Act 2004|ban on foxhunting with dogs in England and Wales]], stating that it did not protect animal welfare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/helen-responds-hunting-act-concerns|title=Helen responds to Hunting Act concerns|last=Whately|first=Helen|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=21 June 2017|publisher=Helen Whately|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225058/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/helen-responds-hunting-act-concerns|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe campaigned with the [[Kent County Council]] for two new schools to be opened in [[Maidstone]], Kent to relieve pressure on primary school places as well as offering more places for children with [[special needs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mps-plea-for-two-new-123039/|title=MP Helen Whately plea for two new schools in Maidstone at Kent Medical Campus|publisher=Kent Online|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=21 June 2017|last=McWethy|first=Claire|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328171758/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mps-plea-for-two-new-123039/|archivedate=28 March 2017}}</ref> This resulted in the opening of Maidstone Primary Academy and the secondary [[Special education in the United Kingdom|special school]], Bearsted Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/two-new-schools-maidstone|title=Two new schools for Maidstone!|publisher=Helen Whately|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=21 June 2017|last=Whately|first=Helen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917213534/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/two-new-schools-maidstone|archivedate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/Bearsted_to_get_its_new_primary_school_-_full_details/|title=Bearsted to get its new primary school&nbsp;\u2014 full details|work=Downs Mail|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|archivedate=26 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126024122/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/Bearsted_to_get_its_new_primary_school_-_full_details/}}</ref>\n\nWhately campaigned against [[Maidstone]]'s Local Plan (a policy document that defines the framework for development in the area until 2031<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/residents/planning/local-plan/what-is-the-local-plan|title=What is the Local Plan?|publisher=Maidstone Borough Council|accessdate=30 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626000120/http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/residents/planning/local-plan/what-is-the-local-plan|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>) as she felt that it did not have enough funding for improvements in infrastructure and roads and could damage local landmarks such as [[Leeds Castle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/government-minister-asked-to-intervene-131921/|title=MP's last minute bid to stop Maidstone's Local Plan|publisher=Kent Online|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=Smith|first=Alan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912131112/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/government-minister-asked-to-intervene-131921/|archivedate=12 September 2017}}</ref> Both Whately and [[Maidstone and The Weald (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone and The Weald]] MP [[Helen Grant (politician)|Helen Grant]] wrote to the then [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]] [[Sajid Javid]] in September 2017 to intervene in the matter, but he declined as he felt that it was a decision that should be made locally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/MP_attempts_halt_on_Local_Plan_for_housing_by_appeal_to_Secretary_of_State/|title=MP attempts halt on Local Plan for housing by appeal to Secretary of State|work=Downs Mail|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130192631/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/MP_attempts_halt_on_Local_Plan_for_housing_by_appeal_to_Secretary_of_State/|archivedate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/local-plan-overcomes-last-ditch-challenge-133075/|title=Maidstone's Local Plan to be decided on after Sajid Javid decides not to intervene|publisher=Kent Online|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=McConnell|first=Ed|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009132019/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/local-plan-overcomes-last-ditch-challenge-133075/|archivedate=9 October 2017}}</ref> [[Maidstone Borough Council]] formally adopted the Local Plan in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/council-backs-maidstone-homes-plan-134278/|title=Maidstone's Local Plan has been adopted|publisher=Kent Online|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=Gazet|first=David|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026001226/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/council-backs-maidstone-homes-plan-134278/|archivedate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhately lives in London and in a village near Faversham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/helen-whately/|title=IPSA record|publisher=IPSA|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015004428/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/helen-whately/|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/mp-evacuates-home-after-flood-183797/|title=Faversham MP Helen Whately forced to evacuate home after flood|publisher=Kent Online|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015005010/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/mp-evacuates-home-after-flood-183797/|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe has been married to Marcus Whately (whom she met at the [[University of Oxford]]) since 2005.<ref name=FMP>{{cite web|url=https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/england-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=helen&firstname_variants=true&lastname=lightwood&yearofmarriage=2005&yearofmarriage_offset=2&yearofbirth=1976&yearofbirth_offset=2|title=Results for England & Wales Marriages 1837\u20132005|publisher=[[Findmypast]]|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/england-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=helen&firstname_variants=true&lastname=lightwood&yearofmarriage=2005&yearofmarriage_offset=2&yearofbirth=1976&yearofbirth_offset=2|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Surrey/> They have three children. Marcus is the founder and co-chief executive officer of an energy company.<ref name=Helen>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/q-helen|title=Q & A with Helen|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203152815/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/q-helen|archivedate=3 December 2017|publisher=Helen Whately|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estover.co.uk/team/ |title=Team |publisher=Estover |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121508/http://www.estover.co.uk/team/ |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref> She has one older brother.<ref name=Down/> Since 2015, she has been a vice-president of the [[Maidstone]] branch of the learning disability charity [[Mencap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/AGM-Final-Report-for-2015.pdf|page=2|title=Annual Report 2015|publisher=[[Mencap]]|accessdate=21 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/AGM-Final-Report-for-2015.pdf|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/2016-Annual-Reveiw.pdf|title=Annual Report 2016|page=2|publisher=Mencap|accessdate=21 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/2016-Annual-Reveiw.pdf|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwca.org.uk/helen-grant/helen-grant-visits-mencap-with-fellow-mps/|publisher=Maidstone and the Weald Conservatives|date=16 November 2015|accessdate=21 June 2017|title=Helen Grant visits Mencap with fellow MPs|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828192638/http://mwca.org.uk/helen-grant/helen-grant-visits-mencap-with-fellow-mps/|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=helen-whately/4527 |publicwhip=Helen_Whately |theywork=helen_whately}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Helen Whately}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]]\n |years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whately, Helen}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:People from Norwich]]\n[[Category:People from Redhill, Surrey]]\n[[Category:People from Faversham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Helen Whately\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Helen Whately MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Department of Health and Social Care (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Social Care]]\n| term_start = 13 February 2020\n| term_end = \n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| predecessor =[[Caroline Dinenage]]  \n| successor =\n| office1 = [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the Arts, Heritage and Tourism]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start1 = 10 September 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/helen-whately|title=Helen Whately MP|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017221121/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/helen-whately|archive-date=17 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| term_end1 = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Rebecca Pow]]\n| successor1 = [[Nigel Huddleston]]\n| office2 = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Deputy Chair of the Conservative Party]]\n| leader2 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start2 = 17 April 2019\n| term_end2 = 10 September 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[James Cleverly]]\n| successor2 = [[Paul Scully]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]]\n| term_start3 = 8 May 2015\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]]\n| successor3 = \n| majority3 = 21,976 (43.6%)<ref name=BBC2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700|publisher=BBC News|title=Faversham & Mid Kent|accessdate=13 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411094752/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_name = Helen Olivia Bicknell Lightwood\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|6|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwich]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Marcus Whately|2005}}\n| children = 3\n| alma_mater = [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n| website = {{url|helenwhately.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Helen Olivia Bicknell Whately'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9123}}</ref> (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Lightwood''';<ref>{{cite news |url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/83953/whately |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 August 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2017 |title=Whately |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205028/http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/83953/whately |archivedate=11 November 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/121365/whately |title=Whately |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 August 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021213/http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/births/121365/whately |archivedate=12 November 2017 }}</ref> born 23 June 1976) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who was appointed  [[Minister of State]] (Minister for Care) at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]] on 13 February 2020 and [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]] since 2015. She also served as Deputy Chair of the Conservative Party.\n\nShe was born in [[Norwich]]. Her early education was at the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Westminster School]] in London. After graduating from the [[University of Oxford]], she worked as a management consultant trainee at [[PriceWaterhouseCoopers]]. From 2007 to 2015, she worked as a management consultant at [[McKinsey & Company]] in their healthcare division.  She was [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Arts, Heritage and Tourism]] from 10 September 2019 until 13 Feb 2020. \n\n==Early life and career==\nHelen Olivia Bicknell Lightwood<ref name=FMP/> was born in [[Norwich]] on 23 June 1976, and grew up near [[Redhill, Surrey]]. Both her parents worked as doctors.<ref name=MyParl>{{cite web |url=http://myparliament.info/member/4527 |title=Biography for Helen Whately |publisher=MyParliament |accessdate=22 April 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428235943/http://myparliament.info/member/4527 |archivedate=28 April 2017 }}</ref><ref name=Down>{{cite news |title=Personality Profile |pages=8\u20139 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109173126/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/_img/pics/pdf_1483564629.pdf |archivedate=9 November 2017 |last=Finlay |first=Simon |url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/_img/pics/pdf_1483564629.pdf |work=Mid Kent Living |accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Surrey>{{cite news |url=http://www.surreycomet.co.uk/news/1358635.conservatives_are_putting_faith_in_youthful_whately/ |title=Conservatives are putting faith in youthful Whately |date=30 April 2007 |work=Surrey Comet |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124083816/http://www.surreycomet.co.uk/news/1358635.conservatives_are_putting_faith_in_youthful_whately/ |archivedate=24 November 2015 }}</ref> She was educated at [[Woldingham School]], Surrey, a day and boarding schools for girls aged 11-18; before entering the [[sixth form]] at the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Westminster School]] in London.<ref name=Down/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/general-election-candidates-for-faversham-35166/ |title=Who wants your vote in Faversham and Mid Kent? |publisher=Kent Online |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815083143/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/general-election-candidates-for-faversham-35166/ |archivedate=15 August 2015 }}</ref> During her school years she undertook work experience in hospitals, with the intention of following her parents into a medical career, but Whately commented in her maiden speech as MP that it instead incentivised her to pursue a career in which she could improve healthcare as a whole.<ref name=maiden/>\n\nAfter leaving school, she taught English in rural [[Nepal]] for a year.<ref name=Surrey/> Lightwood studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]].<ref name=Down/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/Alumni/Prominent-alumni.aspx |title=LMH, Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Prominent Alumni |accessdate=22 May 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512181442/http://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/Alumni/Prominent-alumni.aspx |archivedate=12 May 2015 }}</ref> During her time at Oxford she was a member of debating society the [[Oxford Union]], but she did not have any interest in student politics, later saying that she felt that it \"did not seem to be about getting stuff done\".<ref name=Down/>\n\nAfter university, she worked at [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] for two years as a management consultant trainee before working at [[AOL]] where Lightwood was involved in setting up their internet film service.<ref name=Surrey/><ref>{{cite news|title=A future Tory Cabinet ... at least according to Tatler |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/a-future-tory-cabinet-at-least-according-to-tatler-6898834.html |work=London Evening Standard |date=9 September 2008 |last1=Hopkirk |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Mendick |first2=Robert |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113013809/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/a-future-tory-cabinet-at-least-according-to-tatler-6898834.html |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref><ref name=Helen/> After this she worked as a media policy advisor for the then Shadow Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport and Conservative Party MP [[Hugo Swire]]. This experience inspired her to pursue a political career.<ref name=Down/> In 2008, British society magazine ''[[Tatler]]'' selected Whately as one of ten young rising stars of the Conservative Party and tipped her as a future Health Secretary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Society magazine Tatler unveils line-up of 'top Tory totty'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2711375/Society-magazine-Tatler-unveils-line-up-of-top-Tory-totty.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 September 2008|accessdate=27 June 2019|last=Singh|first=Anita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626232138/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2711375/Society-magazine-Tatler-unveils-line-up-of-top-Tory-totty.html|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe unsuccessfully contested the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] in the [[Kingston and Surbiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston and Surbiton]] constituency for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], losing to the incumbent [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Ed Davey]] by 7,560 votes (13.3%).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c43.stm|title=Kingston & Surbiton|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701045211/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c43.stm|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2007 to 2015, Whately worked as an engagement manager for the management consultancy firm [[McKinsey & Company]] in their healthcare division.<ref name=Helen/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/helen-whately/1202337.bio |work=Health Service Journal |title=Helen Whately |accessdate=21 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828185737/https://www.hsj.co.uk/helen-whately/1202337.bio |archivedate=28 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nWhately was selected by the Conservative Party in February 2015 to contest the [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]] seat in an all-women shortlist.<ref name=\"kentonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/tory-candidate-picked-for-faversham-32433/ |title=Helen Whately to replace Sir Hugh Robertson as conservative candidate for Faversham and Mid Kent |publisher=Kent Online |accessdate=7 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511022350/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/tory-candidate-picked-for-faversham-32433 |archivedate=11 May 2015 |date=25 February 2015 }}</ref> The constituency's previous Conservative MP [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]] had chosen in January not to seek re-election.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30824449 |title=Hugh Robertson, former Conservative minister, to stand down |publisher=BBC News |date=15 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115112801/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30824449 |archivedate=15 January 2015 }}</ref> She had also made the shortlist for the [[Wealden (UK Parliament constituency)|Wealden]], [[North East Hampshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Hampshire]], [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]], [[Bury St. Edmunds (UK Parliament constituency)|Bury St. Edmunds]] and [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury]] constituencies.<ref name=kentonline/>\n\nShe was elected as MP for Faversham and Mid Kent at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with 24,895 votes (54%) and a majority of 16,652 (36.4%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230161528/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |archivedate=30 December 2016 }}</ref> The constituency is considered as a [[safe seat]], and has been represented by Conservative MPs since its creation in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/favershamandmidkent/ |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=UK Polling Report |accessdate=7 November 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108093855/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/favershamandmidkent/ |archivedate=8 November 2017 }}</ref> Whately's maiden speech on 2 June focused on the [[National Health Service]].<ref name=maiden>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/maiden-speech |title=Maiden Speech |publisher=Helen Whately |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |last=Whately |first=Helen |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225644/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/maiden-speech |archivedate=28 August 2017 }}</ref> In July, she was chosen to sit on the Commons [[Health Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/helen-whately/4527 |title=Helen Whately MP |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=14 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906212133/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/helen-whately/4527 |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref> In December, she voted to support Prime Minister [[David Cameron]]'s plans to carry out airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34987921 |title=Syria strikes: Find out how your MP voted |publisher=BBC News |date=3 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203070703/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34987921 |archivedate=3 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nWhately supported the United Kingdom (UK) remaining within the [[European Union]] (EU) in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|June 2016 membership referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough |first1=Tom |title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence? |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/ |accessdate=11 October 2016 |work=The Spectator |date=16 February 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022111657/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/ |archivedate=22 October 2016 }}</ref> She stated her reason for this was that British membership of the EU meant greater economic growth, security, standards of living for British people, and British influence in international affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/why-im-voting-stay-eu |title=Why I'm voting to stay in the EU |publisher=Helen Whately |date=22 May 2017 |last=Whately |first=Helen |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118221921/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/why-im-voting-stay-eu |archivedate=18 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Whately was appointed as the Parliamentary Private Secretary (PPS) to the International Trade Minister [[Greg Hands]].<ref name=Helen/> In October, she was selected as the Chair of the All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) for Mental Health and of the APPG for Fruit and Vegetable Farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/mental-health.htm |title=All-Party Parliamentary Group on Mental Health |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121932/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/mental-health.htm |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentnews.co.uk/news/helen-whately-elected-chair-of-parliamentary-group-for-mental-health-1-4732737 |title=Helen Whately elected chair of parliamentary group for mental health |publisher=Kent News |last=Pyman |first=Tom |date=12 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193724/http://www.kentnews.co.uk/news/helen-whately-elected-chair-of-parliamentary-group-for-mental-health-1-4732737 |archivedate=19 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124235143/https://www.hortweek.com/new-parliamentary-group-hears-fruit-veg-growers-concerns/fresh-produce/article/1414592 |archivedate=24 November 2017 |url=http://www.hortweek.com/new-parliamentary-group-hears-fruit-veg-growers-concerns/fresh-produce/article/1414592 |work=[[Horticulture Week]] |date=4 November 2016 |title=New parliamentary group hears fruit and veg growers' concerns |accessdate=1 April 2017 |last=McEwan |first=Gavin}}</ref> In February 2017, she voted to support the government's motion for the [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoking of Article 50]] to formally start the process of the UK's withdrawal from the EU. Whately, a \"Remain\" supporter, explained her decision as honouring the result of the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/brexit-lets-use-opportunity-frame-countrys-future |title=Brexit: Let's use this opportunity to frame the country's future |publisher=Helen Whately |last=Whately |first=Helen |date=2 February 2017 |accessdate=3 December 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203155243/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/brexit-lets-use-opportunity-frame-countrys-future |archivedate=3 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Article 50 Brexit vote: Full list of MPs who backed Theresa May starting official EU negotiations&nbsp;\u2014 and those who voted against |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-parliament-mps-vote-brexit-theresa-may-eu-negotiations-labour-conservative-how-voted-a7558291.html |work=The Independent |date=1 February 2017 |accessdate=3 December 2017 |last=Batchelor |first=Tom |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032958/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/article-50-parliament-mps-vote-brexit-theresa-may-eu-negotiations-labour-conservative-how-voted-a7558291.html |archivedate=1 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, she faced criticism from some local residents for tweeting enthusiastically about being at the inauguration of President Donald Trump, due to his controversial policies. She responded that she was representing parliamentarians from the UK, and that it was important to build links with key foreign allies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Faversham and Mid Kent MP Helen Whately faces backlash after tweet about Donald Trump's inauguration |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mp-faces-backlash-after-inauguration-119313/ |work=Kent Online |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=22 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015003230/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mp-faces-backlash-after-inauguration-119313/ |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhately held her seat in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]] in June 2017, with 30,390 (61.1%) votes and an increased majority of 17,413 (35%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700 |title=Faversham & Mid Kent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 June 2017 |archivedate=17 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617084859/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000700}}</ref> Following the election she became the PPS to the [[Secretary of State for Education]] and [[Minister for Women and Equalities]], [[Justine Greening]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2017/06/parliamentary-private-secretaries-full-list.html |title=Parliamentary Private Secretaries: full list |publisher=Conservative Home |date=28 June 2017 |accessdate=17 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009063654/https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2017/06/parliamentary-private-secretaries-full-list.html |archivedate=9 October 2017 }}</ref> She also became the chair of the APPG for Health, and Personalised Medicine and continued to be chair of the APPG for Mental Health, and Fruit and Vegetable Farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170928/health.htm |title=Health |publisher=parliament.uk |accessdate=22 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023120212/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170928/health.htm |archivedate=23 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/personalised-medicine.htm |title=Personalised Medicine |accessdate=9 November 2017 |publisher=parliament.uk |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/personalised-medicine.htm |archivedate=9 November 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/register-171108.pdf |title=Register of All-Party Parliamentary Groups |date=8 November 2017 |pages=462, 504, 621, 677 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021330/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/171108/register-171108.pdf |archivedate=12 November 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Whately was criticised for accepting several thousand pounds' worth of hospitality from the [[Saudi Arabian government]] before going on to defend its record in a parliamentary debate. The debate followed an urgent question by Liberal Democrat MP [[Tom Brake]] over fears of the imminent execution of 14 men for protest-related offences, including a number who were children at the time of their alleged offences. Whately had urged parliamentarians to \"appreciate that the government of Saudi Arabia are taking to steps to improve their actions on human rights\", but was criticised by an opposition [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP as a \"serial apologist for the regime\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory MPs push 'soft' policy on Saudi executions months after meeting king |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/xxx-1055620181 |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=Middle East Eye |date=18 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042211/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/xxx-1055620181 |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia has paid for nearly a dozen Tory MPs to fly out and visit on 'fact-finding missions' this year |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/saudi-arabia-has-paid-for-nearly-a-dozen-tory-mps-to-fly-out-and-visit-it-so-far-this-year-a6993271.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=20 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042040/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/saudi-arabia-has-paid-for-nearly-a-dozen-tory-mps-to-fly-out-and-visit-it-so-far-this-year-a6993271.html |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, she was appointed as PPS to [[Brandon Lewis]], the [[Minister without portfolio]] and [[Chairman of the Conservative Party|Conservative Party Chair]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676443/PPS_List_January_2018.pdf |title=Parliamentary Private Secretaries January 2018 |publisher=gov.uk |date=January 2018 |accessdate=5 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507003457/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676443/PPS_List_January_2018.pdf |archive-date=7 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/08/james-brokenshire-resigns-northern-ireland-secretary-cabinet-reshuffle|title=Brandon Lewis unveiled as Tory chairman in chaotic reshuffle|work=The Guardian|date=8 January 2018|access-date=8 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108133601/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/08/james-brokenshire-resigns-northern-ireland-secretary-cabinet-reshuffle|archive-date=8 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later in the year, she became Vice Chair of the Conservative Party for Women, after [[Maria Caulfield]] stood down in protest at the Government's approach to Brexit.<ref name=\"resignation\">{{cite news |title=Tory vice-chairs quit over PM's Brexit plan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44785797 |work=BBC News |date=10 July 2018 |access-date=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427143515/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44785797 |archive-date=27 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/kent-mp-handed-vice-chair-role-187073/|title=Faversham and Mid Kent MP Helen Whately named Conservative's vice-chair for women|publisher=Kent Online|date=27 July 2018|accessdate=25 June 2019|last=Pyman|first=Tom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627131627/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/kent-mp-handed-vice-chair-role-187073/|archive-date=27 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Whately voted for the then Prime Minister Theresa May's Brexit withdrawal agreement. She also stated her opposition to a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|referendum on any Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/how-ive-voted-brexit|publisher=Helen Whately|last=Whately|first=Helen|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=13 September 2019|title=How I've voted on Brexit|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405005440/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/how-ive-voted-brexit|archive-date=5 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 April, Whately was promoted to deputy chair of the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/04/28/tories-braced-local-election-wipeout-deputy-chairman-warns-mounting/|title=Tories braced for local election wipeout as deputy chairman warns of mounting anger on the doorstep|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 April 2019|last=Yorke|first=Harry|accessdate=25 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512113158/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/04/28/tories-braced-local-election-wipeout-deputy-chairman-warns-mounting/|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?id=uk.org.publicwhip/member/41839|publisher=The Public Whip|accessdate=25 June 2019|title=Voting Record \u2014 Helen Whately MP, Faversham and Mid Kent (25398)}}</ref> On 10 September, she was appointed as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] for Arts, Heritage and Tourism by Prime Minister Boris Johnson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-cabinet-reshuffle-mps-ministers-a9099976.html|work=The Independent|date=10 September 2019|title=Boris Johnson has cabinet reshuffle following Brexit-induced resignations|last=Austin|first=Henry|access-date=10 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911200221/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-brexit-cabinet-reshuffle-mps-ministers-a9099976.html|archive-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the December general election, she was re-elected with an increased majority of 21,976 (43.6%)<ref name=BBC2019/>\n\nIn February 2020, Whatley joined the [[Department for Health and Social Care]] as the [[Minister of State for Social Care]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Lydia |last=Catling |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/new-jobs-for-kent-mps-in-government-reshuffle-222102/ |title=Prime Minister Boris Johnson given MPs Helen Whately and Kelly Tolhurst new jobs in government |publisher=Kent Online |date=14 February 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Campaigns===\nIn 2017, she campaigned for the repeal of the [[Hunting Act 2004|ban on foxhunting with dogs in England and Wales]], stating that it did not protect animal welfare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/helen-responds-hunting-act-concerns|title=Helen responds to Hunting Act concerns|last=Whately|first=Helen|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=21 June 2017|publisher=Helen Whately|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225058/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/helen-responds-hunting-act-concerns|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe campaigned with the [[Kent County Council]] for two new schools to be opened in [[Maidstone]], Kent to relieve pressure on primary school places as well as offering more places for children with [[special needs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mps-plea-for-two-new-123039/|title=MP Helen Whately plea for two new schools in Maidstone at Kent Medical Campus|publisher=Kent Online|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=21 June 2017|last=McWethy|first=Claire|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328171758/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/mps-plea-for-two-new-123039/|archivedate=28 March 2017}}</ref> This resulted in the opening of Maidstone Primary Academy and the secondary [[Special education in the United Kingdom|special school]], Bearsted Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/two-new-schools-maidstone|title=Two new schools for Maidstone!|publisher=Helen Whately|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=21 June 2017|last=Whately|first=Helen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917213534/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/two-new-schools-maidstone|archivedate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/Bearsted_to_get_its_new_primary_school_-_full_details/|title=Bearsted to get its new primary school&nbsp;\u2014 full details|work=Downs Mail|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|archivedate=26 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126024122/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/Bearsted_to_get_its_new_primary_school_-_full_details/}}</ref>\n\nWhately campaigned against [[Maidstone]]'s Local Plan (a policy document that defines the framework for development in the area until 2031<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/residents/planning/local-plan/what-is-the-local-plan|title=What is the Local Plan?|publisher=Maidstone Borough Council|accessdate=30 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626000120/http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/residents/planning/local-plan/what-is-the-local-plan|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>) as she felt that it did not have enough funding for improvements in infrastructure and roads and could damage local landmarks such as [[Leeds Castle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/government-minister-asked-to-intervene-131921/|title=MP's last minute bid to stop Maidstone's Local Plan|publisher=Kent Online|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=Smith|first=Alan|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912131112/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/government-minister-asked-to-intervene-131921/|archivedate=12 September 2017}}</ref> Both Whately and [[Maidstone and The Weald (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone and The Weald]] MP [[Helen Grant (politician)|Helen Grant]] wrote to the then [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]] [[Sajid Javid]] in September 2017 to intervene in the matter, but he declined as he felt that it was a decision that should be made locally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/MP_attempts_halt_on_Local_Plan_for_housing_by_appeal_to_Secretary_of_State/|title=MP attempts halt on Local Plan for housing by appeal to Secretary of State|work=Downs Mail|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130192631/http://www.downsmail.co.uk/news_sport/News/MP_attempts_halt_on_Local_Plan_for_housing_by_appeal_to_Secretary_of_State/|archivedate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/local-plan-overcomes-last-ditch-challenge-133075/|title=Maidstone's Local Plan to be decided on after Sajid Javid decides not to intervene|publisher=Kent Online|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=McConnell|first=Ed|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009132019/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/local-plan-overcomes-last-ditch-challenge-133075/|archivedate=9 October 2017}}</ref> [[Maidstone Borough Council]] formally adopted the Local Plan in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/council-backs-maidstone-homes-plan-134278/|title=Maidstone's Local Plan has been adopted|publisher=Kent Online|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=30 November 2017|last=Gazet|first=David|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026001226/http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/council-backs-maidstone-homes-plan-134278/|archivedate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhately lives in London and in a village near Faversham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/helen-whately/|title=IPSA record|publisher=IPSA|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015004428/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/helen-whately/|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/mp-evacuates-home-after-flood-183797/|title=Faversham MP Helen Whately forced to evacuate home after flood|publisher=Kent Online|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015005010/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/faversham/news/mp-evacuates-home-after-flood-183797/|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe has been married to Marcus Whately (whom she met at the [[University of Oxford]]) since 2005.<ref name=FMP>{{cite web|url=https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/england-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=helen&firstname_variants=true&lastname=lightwood&yearofmarriage=2005&yearofmarriage_offset=2&yearofbirth=1976&yearofbirth_offset=2|title=Results for England & Wales Marriages 1837\u20132005|publisher=[[Findmypast]]|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/england-records-in-birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=helen&firstname_variants=true&lastname=lightwood&yearofmarriage=2005&yearofmarriage_offset=2&yearofbirth=1976&yearofbirth_offset=2|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Surrey/> They have three children. Marcus is the founder and co-chief executive officer of an energy company.<ref name=Helen>{{cite web|url=https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/q-helen|title=Q & A with Helen|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203152815/https://www.helenwhately.org.uk/news/q-helen|archivedate=3 December 2017|publisher=Helen Whately|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estover.co.uk/team/ |title=Team |publisher=Estover |accessdate=11 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121508/http://www.estover.co.uk/team/ |archivedate=13 January 2017 }}</ref> She has one older brother.<ref name=Down/> Since 2015, she has been a vice-president of the [[Maidstone]] branch of the learning disability charity [[Mencap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/AGM-Final-Report-for-2015.pdf|page=2|title=Annual Report 2015|publisher=[[Mencap]]|accessdate=21 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/AGM-Final-Report-for-2015.pdf|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/2016-Annual-Reveiw.pdf|title=Annual Report 2016|page=2|publisher=Mencap|accessdate=21 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109202033/https://maidstonemencap.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/2016-Annual-Reveiw.pdf|archivedate=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwca.org.uk/helen-grant/helen-grant-visits-mencap-with-fellow-mps/|publisher=Maidstone and the Weald Conservatives|date=16 November 2015|accessdate=21 June 2017|title=Helen Grant visits Mencap with fellow MPs|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828192638/http://mwca.org.uk/helen-grant/helen-grant-visits-mencap-with-fellow-mps/|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=helen-whately/4527 |publicwhip=Helen_Whately |theywork=helen_whately}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Helen Whately}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Faversham and Mid Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Faversham and Mid Kent]]\n |years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whately, Helen}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:People from Norwich]]\n[[Category:People from Redhill, Surrey]]\n[[Category:People from Faversham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "2.102.205.1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eParliamentary career:Added content.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Whately"}
{"title_page": "Fulk FitzWarin", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Arms of Fitzwarin.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of FitzWarin: ''Quarterly per fess indented argent and gules'' <ref>Arms of Fulk V FitzWarin, St George's [[Roll of Arms]], 1285, briantimms.com, St George's Roll, part 1, no. E69</ref>]]\n'''Fulk III FitzWarin''' (c. 1160\u20131258; ''alias''  Fulke, Fouke, FitzWaryn, FitzWarren, Fitz Warine, etc., [[List of Latinised names|Latinised]] to ''Fulco Filius Warini'', \"Fulk son of Warin\")  was a powerful [[marcher lord]] seated at [[Whittington Castle]] in [[Shropshire]] in England on the border with [[Wales]], and also at [[Alveston]] in [[Gloucestershire]]. He rebelled against [[John, King of England|King John]] (1199\u20131216) from 1200 to 1203,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\">Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British outlaws of literature and history: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), p. 97</ref> mainly over a dispute concerning his familial right to Whittington Castle, and was declared an [[outlaw]].\nHe was the subject of the famous mediaeval [[legend]] or \"ancestral romance\" entitled ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', which relates the story of his life as an outlaw and his struggle to regain his patrimony from the king.<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club, [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up (London 1855)] (Internet Archive).</ref> He founded, between 1221 and 1226,  [[Alberbury Priory]] in Shropshire which he granted to the Augustinian canons of [[Lilleshall]] but later transferred to the [[Order of Grandmont]]. His grandson was [[Fulk V FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin]] (1251\u20131315).<ref>[[George Cokayne|George Edward Cokayne]] ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', ed. Vicary Gibbs; vol. V, p. 495, Baron FitzWarin</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nFulk III was the son of Fulk II FitzWarin (died 1197) by his wife Hawise le Dinan, a daughter and\nco-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">GEC ''Complete Peerage''; vol. V, p. 495, note (c)</ref> Fulk II was a marcher lord of Shropshire,<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 49</ref> the son and heir of [[Fulk I FitzWarin]] (d.1170/1) of Whittington and Alveston, who himself was the son of (i.e. in Norman French ''Fitz'', in modern French ''fils de'') the family's earliest known ancestor, thus deemed the family patriarch, \"Warin of Meer\", from [[Lorraine (duchy)|Lorraine]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/>\n\n===Earliest ancestry===\nWarin of Meer the patriarch is however a \"shadowy or [[myth]]ical figure\",<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/>  about whom little is certain. The later mediaeval romance ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'' gives his name as \"Warin de Meer\".  Whatever his true place of origin it is however generally believed that the head of the Warin family came to England during the reign of [[William the Conqueror]] (1066\u20131087). Neither the father nor his sons were during that reign [[tenant-in-chief|tenants-in-chief]], that is to say important [[vassal]]s or [[English feudal barony|feudal barons]], rather their grants of lands were obtained from later kings.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 34</ref>\n\nFulk I (d.1170/1) was rewarded by King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189) for his support of his mother [[Empress Matilda]] in [[The Anarchy|her civil war]] with [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154) and conferred to him in 1153 the royal [[manor]] of [[Alveston]] in Gloucestershire and in 1149 the manor of Whadborough (in [[Loddington, Leicestershire|Loddington]]<ref>J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Vol. 3 part 1: East Goscote Hundred (John Nichols, London 1800), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000032377095&view=1up&seq=476 pp. 332-34] (Hathi Trust).</ref>), Leicestershire. Fulk II [[Feudal land tenure in England|held]] those properties after the death of his father in 1171.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 34, 35</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Land dispute===\nAt some time before 1178 Fulk II (d. 1197) married  Hawise de Dinan, a wealthy heiress, a daughter and co-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]], who held [[Ludlow Castle]] in the Welsh Marches for the Empress Matilda during the civil war between herself and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]].<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zvzWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PAxi p. xi] (Google, no preview).</ref> Throughout his lifetime he encountered numerous problems in receiving his patrimony and his other claims to land. These land disputes included estates his father held [[Tenant-in-chief|in-chief]] from the crown and others which he had held from the Peverel family as [[Lord|overlords]].\n\nOther lawsuits concerned Whittington Castle held by the Peverels during the reign of King Stephen. Although he won the right to Whittington in or about 1195, he never received formal legal ''[[seisin]]'' and it remained in Welsh hands at the time of his death in 1197.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 35</ref>\n\n[[Whittington Castle]] lies on the English side of [[Offa's Dyke]], which during the Norman era and before was the border between England and [[Wales]]. The site was fortified as a castle by [[William Peverel]] in 1138, in support of Empress Matilda, the daughter of King [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] (1100\u20131135), in her struggle (known as [[The Anarchy]]) for the throne against King Stephen (1135\u20131154), grandson of [[William the Conqueror]]. In the late 1140s the [[Marcher lord|lordship]] of [[Whittington, Shropshire|Whittington]], like [[Oswestry]] and Overton ceased to be part of England and became part of the [[Kingdom of Powys]] and a Welsh [[marcher lord]]ship.<ref>P. Brown, P. King, and P. Remfry, 'Whittington Castle: The marcher fortress of the Fitz Warin family', Shropshire Archaeology and History LXXIX (2004), 106\u2013127.</ref>  In 1165 [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] granted the castle of Whittington on [[Roger de Powis]], a Welsh leader, to whom he gave funds for its repair in about 1173.<ref>D. Stephenson, ''Medieval Powys: Kingdom, Principality and Lordships, 1132-1293'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ERJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA286#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 286] (Google); citing F. Suppe, 'Roger of Powys, Henry II's Anglo-Welsh Middleman, and His Lineage', ''The Welsh History Review'', Vol. 21 part 1 (2002), pp. 1-23.</ref> Roger de Powis was followed by his son Meurig (or Maurice), who was followed by his son Werennoc. A rival claim was made by Fulk III FitzWarin (c. 1160\u20131258).<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\">Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 52</ref>\n\n===Rebellions===\nFulk III continued the claim to Whittington made by his father. After his father's death in 1197 Fulk III offered [[feudal relief|relief]] of \u00a3100 for the inheritance of Whittington. However Maurice of Powis (d.1200), the son of Roger of Powis, who had offered half that amount, on 11 April 1200 was granted Whittington by [[John, King of England|King John]]. Again, after Maurice's death in August 1200, King John granted it to Maurice's heirs.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 36</ref>\n\nIt is not known why King John refused to recognise Fulk's claim to Whittington as his rightful inheritance but by April 1201 Fulk was in open rebellion against the King. He was accompanied by approximately fifty-two followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, his cousins, and by the family's many tenants and allies in the Marches.<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\"/>\n\nFulk's rebellion is not related in detail by chroniclers but was clearly considerable as in the spring of 1201, while King John crossed into [[Normandy]] and [[Poitou]] to suppress a revolt by the [[Lusignan dynasty|Lusignans]],<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 157</ref> he ordered [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent|Hubert de Burgh]], with 100 knights, to counter the rebellion of Fulk and William Marsh, a [[Somerset]]shire knight who was raiding shipping off the coast of [[Devon]].<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pp. 48, 84</ref>\n\nIn July 1202 Fulk and his men are reported to have taken refuge in [[Stanley Abbey]] in Wiltshire. Another man, Gilbert de Duure, is mentioned in records as \"...having been an outlaw associated with Fulk Fitz Warin\".  Yet another, Eustace de Kivilly, was pardoned earlier in 1202 by King John for \"being associated with Fulk\".<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 38</ref>\n\nAfter many years of being an outlaw, on 11 November 1203 Fulk was pardoned together with over thirty of his followers, including his brothers William,  Phillip and John and his cousins. In October 1204, on payment of a fine of 200 marks, Fulk at last received \"right and inheritance\" in Whittington.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), p. xii.</ref> Whittington Castle thereafter descended in the [[Baron FitzWarin|FitzWarin family]], all subsequent holders bearing the first-name Fulk, until the death of [[Fulk XI FitzWarin, 7th Baron FitzWarin]] (1405\u20131420) in 1420.<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pps. 51\u201352</ref>\n\nIn 1207 Fulk III was clearly highly regarded by many of the king's barons as evidenced by the identity of men known to have provided surety for Fulk's fine of 1,200 marks to marry the heiress daughter of Robert le Vavasur. The suretors included the Peverels, [[Alan Basset]], [[William de Braose (died 1230)|William de Braose]] (d.1230), a de Lacy, [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury]] and [[Henry de Bohun, 1st Earl of Hereford]].<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 39</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 1214, when King John again set sail for [[Poitou]], Fulk was among the barons who accompanied him. He is believed then to have been  a vassal of [[Geoffrey FitzGeoffrey de Mandeville, 2nd Earl of Essex|Geoffrey de Mandeville]], Earl of Gloucester.<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pp. 280, 294.</ref>\n\nIn 1215 Fulk was one of many giving great trouble to the [[Sheriff of Shropshire]]. Before 1216 and the accession of the infant King [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (1216\u20131272), John's son, Fulk's manor of Alveston had been seized by the crown and in the following year 1217 all of his other lands in Gloucestershire were likewise seized. By 1218 however Fulk had made peace and his lands were ordered restored by the regents of [[Henry III of England|Henry III]].<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 41, 43</ref>\n\nBy 1220 Fulk had regained some favour with the young King Henry III and had been allowed to rebuild and fortify Whittington. In 1223 however it fell to [[Llywelyn the Great]], prince of Wales. Fulk  regained it the following year although his disputes with Llywelyn continued and more of Fulk's lands were seized.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 42</ref>\n\nBy 1228 a truce seems to have been reached between Fulk and Llywelyn following the intervention of the king.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 41</ref>\n\nThroughout these years Fulk's relations with the King were changeable and seemed to be directly dependent on the state of affairs in Wales. As a marcher lord Fulk's role as a protector of the English border against the Welsh was vital to the English King. He arbitrated several border disputes on behalf of the King and although there were more personal disagreements, there were no more rebellions on the part of Fulk III.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 42, 43, 45</ref>\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\nFulk III FitzWarin married twice:\n*Firstly, in about 1207, to [[Maud le Vavasour, Baroness Butler|Maud le Vavasour]] (d.1226), (''alias'' Matilda), daughter of Robert le Vavasour and widow of the powerful Lancashire baron Theobald Walter.<ref>George Edward Cokayne, The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant, ed. Vicary Gibbs, Vol. II (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1912). p. 448</ref> He secured pledges for the marriage from his brother William and from Maud's father, Robert le Vavasour, who was a tenant of the [[English feudal barony|feudal barony]] of [[Skipton]] in Yorkshire.<ref>Max Lieberman, ''The Medieval Marches of Wales: The Creation and perception of a Frontier, 1066'' (Cambridge University Press 2010), p 87-97</ref><ref>Emma Cavell, \u201cThe Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,\u201d Thirteenth Century England XI, eds. Bj\u00f6rn Weiler; Janet Burton; Phillipp Schofield & Karen St\u00f6ber, Woodbridge, UK: The Boydell Press, 2007, p. 174 & note 2.</ref> Maud died in 1226 and was buried at her husband's foundation [[Alberbury Priory]] (''alias'' New Abbey, Alberbury) in Shropshire.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\">Emma Cavell, \u201cThe Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,\u201d Thirteenth Century England XI, eds. Bj\u00f6rn Weiler; Janet Burton; Phillipp Schofield & Karen St\u00f6ber, Woodbridge, UK: The Boydell Press, 2007, p. 174 & n. 2.</ref><ref>Sir Bernard Burke, C.B., LL.D., Ulster King of Arms, Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire, Burke's Peerage/Genealogical Publishing Co., 1883, Reprinted 1985. 1996, p. 213</ref><ref>George Edward Cokayne, The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant, The Hon. Vicary Gibbs, London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., Volume II Bass to Canning, 1912, p. 448.</ref> He had the following progeny by Maud le Vavasour:\n\n#Fulk IV FitzWarin (d.1264)<ref name=\"BWF37\">Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Waren Families, 1066\u20131272'' (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1944), p. 37</ref>\n#Fulk Glas<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Hawise FitzWarin, wife of William Pantulf, a [[Marcher Lord]]<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Joan FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Eva FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n\n*Fulk married secondly to Clarice de Auberville, daughter and heiress of [[Robert de Auberville]] of Iden and Iham, Sussex, and his wife Claricia de Gestling. The progeny from this second marriage appears to have been a single surviving daughter:\n\n#Mabel FitzWarin (\u22121297), who married 1stly William de Crevequer (no issue), and 2ndly John de Tregoz, Lord Tregoz (d. before 6 Sept 1300), by whom she had two daughters and coheirs, Clarice and Sybil<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n\n==Death & burial==\nFulk III lived to a great age and at some time before his death in 1258, he handed over control of much of his responsibilities to his son and heir Fulk IV. In 1252 he made his will in which he stated his wish to be buried at the priory he founded, Alberbury Priory.<ref>''[http://www.discovershropshire.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/theme:20070423145036 Discover Shropshire'']''</ref>\n\n==Romance of ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''==\nAfter Foulk's death he became the subject the famous \"ancestral romance\" known as '''''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''''', which contains a highly embellished account of his life and family history.<ref>Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L. Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), pp. 99\u201399</ref>\n\nThe biography of Fulk III survives in a French prose \"ancestral [[romance (heroic literature)|romance]]\", extant in a  manuscript containing English, French and [[Latin]] texts, which is based on a lost French verse romance.<ref>The French verse form was seen by Leland: T. Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', 2nd, enlarged edition, 6 vols (W. and J. Richardson, London 1770), I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=376 pp. 236-37, representing fols. 268-69] (Hathi Trust).</ref> A 16th-century summary by [[John Leland]] of an otherwise lost [[Middle English]] verse version, ''The Nobile Actes of the Guarines'', has also been preserved.<ref>Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=370 pp. 230-36, representing fols. 261-68] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The work is part of the [[Matter of England]].<ref name=boundaries>Neil Cartlidge ''Boundaries in Medieval Romance'',  D. S. Brewer, 2008, {{ISBN|1-84384-155-X}}, 9781843841555. pp. 29\u201342</ref> The outline of the work is as follows. As a young boy, Fulk was sent to the court of King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189), where he grew up with the king's younger son, the future King [[John of England|John]] (1199\u20131216). John became his enemy after a childhood quarrel during a game of chess. As an adult, King John retained his animosity toward Fulk whom he stripped of his ancestral holdings. Fulk thereupon took to the woods as an outlaw and lived a life of adventure. The story may in fact  have confused aspects of the lives of two FitzWarins, Fulk I (d. 1171) and Fulk II (d. 1197), father and son. The romance of Fulk FitzWarin is noted for its parallels to the legend of [[Robin Hood]].<ref>Introduction to ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', edited by Stephen Knight and Thomas H. Ohlgren, originally published in ''Robin Hood and Other Outlaw Tales'', Kalamazoo, Michigan: Medieval Institute Publications, 1997.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography;;, 2004, Vol. \"F\", pp.&nbsp;953\u20134, FitzWarin family\n*Dolmans, Emily (2016) \"Locating the Border: Britain and the Welsh Marches in Fouke le Fitz Waryn\". In Laura Ashe, Wendy Scase and David Lawton (eds.), [https://boydellandbrewer.com/new-medieval-literatures-16-hb.html \"New Medieval Literatures 16\"] (109\u2013134). Boydell & Brewer. {{ISBN|9781843844334}}\n*Rock, Catherine A. (2011) \"Fouke le Fitz Waryn and King John: Rebellion and Reconciliation\". In Alexander L. Kaufman (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ogTytW5dZKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: Essays on Medieval and Early Modern Figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'']. Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co.  {{ISBN|0-7864-5877-1}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=bYIDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1252&lpg=PA1252&dq=%22de+livet%22+dublin&source=web&ots=mClUNzBDQS&sig=50w17k8PaYrxlA2GuupMhwHKQkw&hl=en#PPA1253,M1 \"L'Histoire de Foulques FitzWarin\", ''A Treatise on the Law of Landlord and Tenant, as Administered in Ireland'', John Smith Furlong, 1845]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft_djvu.txt Wright, Thomas, (ed.) ''The History of Fulk FitzWarin, an Outlawed Baron, in the Reign of King John''. Edited from a Manuscript Preserved in the British Museum, with an English Translation and Illustrative Notes, London, 1855, Printed for the Warton Club]. pp.&nbsp;1\u2013183 text, pp.&nbsp;183\u2013231 notes.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk Fitzwarin}}\n[[Category:1160s births]]\n[[Category:1258 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:13th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:English heroic legends]]\n[[Category:English outlaws|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:English rebels]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:People from Shropshire|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Marcher lords]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Alveston]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Arms of Fitzwarin.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of FitzWarin: ''Quarterly per fess indented argent and gules'' <ref>Arms of Fulk V FitzWarin, St George's [[Roll of Arms]], 1285, briantimms.com, St George's Roll, part 1, no. E69</ref>]]\n'''Fulk III FitzWarin''' (c. 1160\u20131258; ''alias''  Fulke, Fouke, FitzWaryn, FitzWarren, Fitz Warine, etc., [[List of Latinised names|Latinised]] to ''Fulco Filius Warini'', \"Fulk son of Warin\")  was a powerful [[marcher lord]] seated at [[Whittington Castle]] in [[Shropshire]] in England on the border with [[Wales]], and also at [[Alveston]] in [[Gloucestershire]]. He rebelled against [[John, King of England|King John]] (1199\u20131216) from 1200 to 1203,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\">Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British outlaws of literature and history: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), p. 97</ref> mainly over a dispute concerning his familial right to Whittington Castle, and was declared an [[outlaw]].\nHe was the subject of the famous mediaeval [[legend]] or \"ancestral romance\" entitled ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', which relates the story of his life as an outlaw and his struggle to regain his patrimony from the king. He founded, between 1221 and 1226,  [[Alberbury Priory]] in Shropshire which he granted to the Augustinian canons of [[Lilleshall]] but later transferred to the [[Order of Grandmont]]. His grandson was [[Fulk V FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin]] (1251\u20131315).<ref>[[George Cokayne|George Edward Cokayne]] ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', ed. Vicary Gibbs; vol. V, p. 495, Baron FitzWarin</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nFulk III was the son of Fulk II FitzWarin (died 1197) by his wife Hawise le Dinan, a daughter and\nco-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">GEC ''Complete Peerage''; vol. V, p. 495, note (c)</ref> Fulk II was a marcher lord of Shropshire,<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 49</ref> the son and heir of [[Fulk I FitzWarin]] (d.1170/1) of Whittington and Alveston, who himself was the son of (i.e. in Norman French ''Fitz'', in modern French ''fils de'') the family's earliest known ancestor, thus deemed the family patriarch, \"Warin of Meer\", from [[Lorraine (duchy)|Lorraine]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/>\n\n===Earliest ancestry===\nWarin of Meer the patriarch is however a \"shadowy or [[myth]]ical figure\",<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/>  about whom little is certain. The later mediaeval romance ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'' gives his name as \"Warin de Meer\".  Whatever his true place of origin it is however generally believed that the head of the Warin family came to England during the reign of [[William the Conqueror]] (1066\u20131087). Neither the father nor his sons were during that reign [[tenant-in-chief|tenants-in-chief]], that is to say important [[vassal]]s or [[English feudal barony|feudal barons]], rather their grants of lands were obtained from later kings.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 34</ref>\n\nFulk I (d.1170/1) was rewarded by King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189) for his support of his mother [[Empress Matilda]] in [[The Anarchy|her civil war]] with [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154) and conferred to him in 1153 the royal [[manor]] of [[Alveston]] in Gloucestershire and in 1149 the manor of Whadborough (in [[Loddington, Leicestershire|Loddington]]<ref>J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Vol. 3 part 1: East Goscote Hundred (John Nichols, London 1800), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000032377095&view=1up&seq=476 pp. 332-34] (Hathi Trust).</ref>), Leicestershire. Fulk II [[Feudal land tenure in England|held]] those properties after the death of his father in 1171.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 34, 35</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Land dispute===\nAt some time before 1178 Fulk II (d. 1197) married  Hawise de Dinan, a wealthy heiress, a daughter and co-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]], who held [[Ludlow Castle]] in the Welsh Marches for the Empress Matilda during the civil war between herself and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]].<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zvzWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PAxi p. xi] (Google, no preview).</ref> Throughout his lifetime he encountered numerous problems in receiving his patrimony and his other claims to land. These land disputes included estates his father held [[Tenant-in-chief|in-chief]] from the crown and others which he had held from the Peverel family as [[Lord|overlords]].\n\nOther lawsuits concerned Whittington Castle held by the Peverels during the reign of King Stephen. Although he won the right to Whittington in or about 1195, he never received formal legal ''[[seisin]]'' and it remained in Welsh hands at the time of his death in 1197.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 35</ref>\n\n[[Whittington Castle]] lies on the English side of [[Offa's Dyke]], which during the Norman era and before was the border between England and [[Wales]]. The site was fortified as a castle by [[William Peverel]] in 1138, in support of Empress Matilda, the daughter of King [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] (1100\u20131135), in her struggle (known as [[The Anarchy]]) for the throne against King Stephen (1135\u20131154), grandson of [[William the Conqueror]]. In the late 1140s the [[Marcher lord|lordship]] of [[Whittington, Shropshire|Whittington]], like [[Oswestry]] and Overton ceased to be part of England and became part of the [[Kingdom of Powys]] and a Welsh [[marcher lord]]ship.<ref>P. Brown, P. King, and P. Remfry, 'Whittington Castle: The marcher fortress of the Fitz Warin family', Shropshire Archaeology and History LXXIX (2004), 106\u2013127.</ref>  In 1165 [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] granted the castle of Whittington on [[Roger de Powis]], a Welsh leader, to whom he gave funds for its repair in about 1173.<ref>D. Stephenson, ''Medieval Powys: Kingdom, Principality and Lordships, 1132-1293'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ERJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA286#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 286] (Google); citing F. Suppe, 'Roger of Powys, Henry II's Anglo-Welsh Middleman, and His Lineage', ''The Welsh History Review'', Vol. 21 part 1 (2002), pp. 1-23.</ref> Roger de Powis was followed by his son Meurig (or Maurice), who was followed by his son Werennoc. A rival claim was made by Fulk III FitzWarin (c. 1160\u20131258).<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\">Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 52</ref>\n\n===Rebellions===\nFulk III continued the claim to Whittington made by his father. After his father's death in 1197 Fulk III offered [[feudal relief|relief]] of \u00a3100 for the inheritance of Whittington. However Maurice of Powis (d.1200), the son of Roger of Powis, who had offered half that amount, on 11 April 1200 was granted Whittington by [[John, King of England|King John]]. Again, after Maurice's death in August 1200, King John granted it to Maurice's heirs.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 36</ref>\n\nIt is not known why King John refused to recognise Fulk's claim to Whittington as his rightful inheritance but by April 1201 Fulk was in open rebellion against the King. He was accompanied by approximately fifty-two followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, his cousins, and by the family's many tenants and allies in the Marches.<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\"/>\n\nFulk's rebellion is not related in detail by chroniclers but was clearly considerable as in the spring of 1201, while King John crossed into [[Normandy]] and [[Poitou]] to suppress a revolt by the [[Lusignan dynasty|Lusignans]],<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) p. 157</ref> he ordered [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent|Hubert de Burgh]], with 100 knights, to counter the rebellion of Fulk and William Marsh, a [[Somerset]]shire knight who was raiding shipping off the coast of [[Devon]].<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pp. 48, 84</ref>\n\nIn July 1202 Fulk and his men are reported to have taken refuge in [[Stanley Abbey]] in Wiltshire. Another man, Gilbert de Duure, is mentioned in records as \"...having been an outlaw associated with Fulk Fitz Warin\".  Yet another, Eustace de Kivilly, was pardoned earlier in 1202 by King John for \"being associated with Fulk\".<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 38</ref>\n\nAfter many years of being an outlaw, on 11 November 1203 Fulk was pardoned together with over thirty of his followers, including his brothers William,  Phillip and John and his cousins. In October 1204, on payment of a fine of 200 marks, Fulk at last received \"right and inheritance\" in Whittington.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), p. xii.</ref> Whittington Castle thereafter descended in the [[Baron FitzWarin|FitzWarin family]], all subsequent holders bearing the first-name Fulk, until the death of [[Fulk XI FitzWarin, 7th Baron FitzWarin]] (1405\u20131420) in 1420.<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pps. 51\u201352</ref>\n\nIn 1207 Fulk III was clearly highly regarded by many of the king's barons as evidenced by the identity of men known to have provided surety for Fulk's fine of 1,200 marks to marry the heiress daughter of Robert le Vavasur. The suretors included the Peverels, [[Alan Basset]], [[William de Braose (died 1230)|William de Braose]] (d.1230), a de Lacy, [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury]] and [[Henry de Bohun, 1st Earl of Hereford]].<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 39</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 1214, when King John again set sail for [[Poitou]], Fulk was among the barons who accompanied him. He is believed then to have been  a vassal of [[Geoffrey FitzGeoffrey de Mandeville, 2nd Earl of Essex|Geoffrey de Mandeville]], Earl of Gloucester.<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore, The Johns Hopkins Press 1964) pp. 280, 294.</ref>\n\nIn 1215 Fulk was one of many giving great trouble to the [[Sheriff of Shropshire]]. Before 1216 and the accession of the infant King [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (1216\u20131272), John's son, Fulk's manor of Alveston had been seized by the crown and in the following year 1217 all of his other lands in Gloucestershire were likewise seized. By 1218 however Fulk had made peace and his lands were ordered restored by the regents of [[Henry III of England|Henry III]].<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 41, 43</ref>\n\nBy 1220 Fulk had regained some favour with the young King Henry III and had been allowed to rebuild and fortify Whittington. In 1223 however it fell to [[Llywelyn the Great]], prince of Wales. Fulk  regained it the following year although his disputes with Llywelyn continued and more of Fulk's lands were seized.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 42</ref>\n\nBy 1228 a truce seems to have been reached between Fulk and Llywelyn following the intervention of the king.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 41</ref>\n\nThroughout these years Fulk's relations with the King were changeable and seemed to be directly dependent on the state of affairs in Wales. As a marcher lord Fulk's role as a protector of the English border against the Welsh was vital to the English King. He arbitrated several border disputes on behalf of the King and although there were more personal disagreements, there were no more rebellions on the part of Fulk III.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), pp. 42, 43, 45</ref>\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\nFulk III FitzWarin married twice:\n*Firstly, in about 1207, to [[Maud le Vavasour, Baroness Butler|Maud le Vavasour]] (d.1226), (''alias'' Matilda), daughter of Robert le Vavasour and widow of the powerful Lancashire baron Theobald Walter.<ref>George Edward Cokayne, The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant, ed. Vicary Gibbs, Vol. II (London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., 1912). p. 448</ref> He secured pledges for the marriage from his brother William and from Maud's father, Robert le Vavasour, who was a tenant of the [[English feudal barony|feudal barony]] of [[Skipton]] in Yorkshire.<ref>Max Lieberman, ''The Medieval Marches of Wales: The Creation and perception of a Frontier, 1066'' (Cambridge University Press 2010), p 87-97</ref><ref>Emma Cavell, \u201cThe Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,\u201d Thirteenth Century England XI, eds. Bj\u00f6rn Weiler; Janet Burton; Phillipp Schofield & Karen St\u00f6ber, Woodbridge, UK: The Boydell Press, 2007, p. 174 & note 2.</ref> Maud died in 1226 and was buried at her husband's foundation [[Alberbury Priory]] (''alias'' New Abbey, Alberbury) in Shropshire.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\">Emma Cavell, \u201cThe Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,\u201d Thirteenth Century England XI, eds. Bj\u00f6rn Weiler; Janet Burton; Phillipp Schofield & Karen St\u00f6ber, Woodbridge, UK: The Boydell Press, 2007, p. 174 & n. 2.</ref><ref>Sir Bernard Burke, C.B., LL.D., Ulster King of Arms, Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire, Burke's Peerage/Genealogical Publishing Co., 1883, Reprinted 1985. 1996, p. 213</ref><ref>George Edward Cokayne, The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant, The Hon. Vicary Gibbs, London: The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., Volume II Bass to Canning, 1912, p. 448.</ref> He had the following progeny by Maud le Vavasour:\n\n#Fulk IV FitzWarin (d.1264)<ref name=\"BWF37\">Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Waren Families, 1066\u20131272'' (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1944), p. 37</ref>\n#Fulk Glas<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Hawise FitzWarin, wife of William Pantulf, a [[Marcher Lord]]<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Joan FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n#Eva FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n\n*Fulk married secondly to Clarice de Auberville, daughter and heiress of [[Robert de Auberville]] of Iden and Iham, Sussex, and his wife Claricia de Gestling. The progeny from this second marriage appears to have been a single surviving daughter:\n\n#Mabel FitzWarin (\u22121297), who married 1stly William de Crevequer (no issue), and 2ndly John de Tregoz, Lord Tregoz (d. before 6 Sept 1300), by whom she had two daughters and coheirs, Clarice and Sybil<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n\n==Death & burial==\nFulk III lived to a great age and at some time before his death in 1258, he handed over control of much of his responsibilities to his son and heir Fulk IV. In 1252 he made his will in which he stated his wish to be buried at the priory he founded, Alberbury Priory.<ref>''[http://www.discovershropshire.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/theme:20070423145036 Discover Shropshire'']''</ref>\n\n==Romance of ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''==\nAfter Foulk's death he became the subject the famous \"ancestral romance\" known as '''''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''''', which contains a highly embellished account of his life and family history.<ref>Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L. Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), pp. 99\u201399</ref>\n\nThe biography of Fulk III survives in a French prose \"ancestral [[romance (heroic literature)|romance]]\", extant in a  manuscript containing English, French and [[Latin]] texts, which is based on a lost French verse romance.<ref>The French verse form was seen by Leland: T. Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', 2nd, enlarged edition, 6 vols (W. and J. Richardson, London 1770), I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=376 pp. 236-37, representing fols. 268-69] (Hathi Trust).</ref> A 16th-century summary by [[John Leland]] of an otherwise lost [[Middle English]] verse version, ''The Nobile Actes of the Guarines'', has also been preserved.<ref>Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=370 pp. 230-36, representing fols. 261-68] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The work is part of the [[Matter of England]].<ref name=boundaries>Neil Cartlidge ''Boundaries in Medieval Romance'',  D. S. Brewer, 2008, {{ISBN|1-84384-155-X}}, 9781843841555. pp. 29\u201342</ref> The outline of the work is as follows. As a young boy, Fulk was sent to the court of King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189), where he grew up with the king's younger son, the future King [[John of England|John]] (1199\u20131216). John became his enemy after a childhood quarrel during a game of chess. As an adult, King John retained his animosity toward Fulk whom he stripped of his ancestral holdings. Fulk thereupon took to the woods as an outlaw and lived a life of adventure. The story may in fact  have confused aspects of the lives of two FitzWarins, Fulk I (d. 1171) and Fulk II (d. 1197), father and son. The romance of Fulk FitzWarin is noted for its parallels to the legend of [[Robin Hood]].<ref>Introduction to ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', edited by Stephen Knight and Thomas H. Ohlgren, originally published in ''Robin Hood and Other Outlaw Tales'', Kalamazoo, Michigan: Medieval Institute Publications, 1997.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography;;, 2004, Vol. \"F\", pp.&nbsp;953\u20134, FitzWarin family\n*Dolmans, Emily (2016) \"Locating the Border: Britain and the Welsh Marches in Fouke le Fitz Waryn\". In Laura Ashe, Wendy Scase and David Lawton (eds.), [https://boydellandbrewer.com/new-medieval-literatures-16-hb.html \"New Medieval Literatures 16\"] (109\u2013134). Boydell & Brewer. {{ISBN|9781843844334}}\n*Rock, Catherine A. (2011) \"Fouke le Fitz Waryn and King John: Rebellion and Reconciliation\". In Alexander L. Kaufman (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ogTytW5dZKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: Essays on Medieval and Early Modern Figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'']. Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co.  {{ISBN|0-7864-5877-1}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=bYIDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1252&lpg=PA1252&dq=%22de+livet%22+dublin&source=web&ots=mClUNzBDQS&sig=50w17k8PaYrxlA2GuupMhwHKQkw&hl=en#PPA1253,M1 \"L'Histoire de Foulques FitzWarin\", ''A Treatise on the Law of Landlord and Tenant, as Administered in Ireland'', John Smith Furlong, 1845]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft_djvu.txt Wright, Thomas, (ed.) ''The History of Fulk FitzWarin, an Outlawed Baron, in the Reign of King John''. Edited from a Manuscript Preserved in the British Museum, with an English Translation and Illustrative Notes, London, 1855, Printed for the Warton Club]. pp.&nbsp;1\u2013183 text, pp.&nbsp;183\u2013231 notes.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk Fitzwarin}}\n[[Category:1160s births]]\n[[Category:1258 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:13th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:English heroic legends]]\n[[Category:English outlaws|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:English rebels]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:People from Shropshire|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Marcher lords]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Alveston]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "best ref up front", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fulk_FitzWarin"}
